{DIALOGUE}: Okay, I give up.
{DIALOGUE}: Where are you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP – BUSH AT EDGE OF SIDEWALK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Mary's face peering out from the leaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Over here in the hydrangea bushes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND MARY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George walks toward the bush.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Here you are.
{DIALOGUE}: Catch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is about to throw her the robe, when a thought strikes him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Wait a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: What am I doing?
{DIALOGUE}: This is a very interesting situation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (from the bushes)
{DIALOGUE}: Please give me my robe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hmm... A man doesn't get in a situation like this every day.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (impatiently)
{DIALOGUE}: I'd like to have my robe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Not in Bedford Falls, anyway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary thrashes around in the bushes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear her say:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Ouch!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Gesundheit.
{DIALOGUE}: This requires a little thought here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (getting mad)
{DIALOGUE}: George Bailey!
{DIALOGUE}: Give me my robe!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I've heard about things like this, but I've never...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Shame on you.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to tell your mother on you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, my mother's way up the corner there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (desperate)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll call the police.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: They're way downtown.
{DIALOGUE}: They'd be on my side, too.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to scream!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (thoughtfully)
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe I could sell tickets.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's see.
{DIALOGUE}: No, the point is, in order to get this robe... I've got it!
{DIALOGUE}: I'll make a deal with you, Mary.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Headlights flash into the scene, and the old Bailey automobile drives in, with Harry at the wheel, and Uncle Billy beside him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: Come on home, quick!
{DIALOGUE}: Your father's had a stroke!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George throws Mary's robe over the bush and gets into the car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary... Mary, I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: I've got to go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, George, let's hurry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Did you get a doctor?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, Campbell's there now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP – THE HYDRANGEA BUSH
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the car drives off, Mary, now wearing the robe, rises up from the bush and follows the car with her eyes.
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT
{META_DATA}: FADE IN:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BAILEY BUILDING AND LOAN SIGN OVER ENTRANCE
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BAILEY BUILDING AND LOAN OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – DIRECTORS MEETING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are about twelve directors seated around a long table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are the substantial citizens of Bedford Falls: Dr. Campbell, a lawyer, an insurance agent, a real estate salesman, etc.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Prominently seated among them is Henry F. Potter, his goon beside his wheelchair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy and George are seated among the directors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chairman of the Board is Dr. Campbell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They have folders and papers before them, on which they have been reporting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before each of the directors there are individual reports for them to study.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: I think that's all we'll need you for, George.
{DIALOGUE}: I know you're anxious to make a train.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (rising)
{DIALOGUE}: I have a taxi waiting downstairs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: I want the Board to know that George gave up his trip to Europe to help straighten things out here these past few months.
{DIALOGUE}: Good luck to you at school, George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: Now we come to the real purpose of this meeting – to appoint a successor to our dear friend, Peter Bailey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Chairman, I'd like to get to my real purpose.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Wait just a minute now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Wait for what?
{DIALOGUE}: I claim this institution is not necessary to this town.
{DIALOGUE}: Therefore, Mr. Chairman, I make a motion to dissolve this institution and turn its assets and liabilities over to the receiver.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (angrily)
{DIALOGUE}: George, you hear what that buzzard...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LAWYER
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Chairman, it's too soon after Peter Bailey's death to discuss chloroforming the Building and Loan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Peter Bailey died three months ago.
{DIALOGUE}: I second Mr. Potter's motion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: Very well.
{DIALOGUE}: In that case I'll ask the two executive officers to withdraw.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dr. Campbell rises from his seat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Uncle Billy start to collect their papers and leave the table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: But before you go, I'm sure the whole board wishes to express its deep sorrow at the passing of Peter Bailey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you very much.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: It was his faith and devotion that are responsible for this organization.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: I'll go further than that.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll say that to the public Peter Bailey was the Building and Loan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everyone looks at him surprised.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (trying to control himself)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, that's fine, Potter, coming from you, considering that you probably drove him to his grave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Peter Bailey was not a business man.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what killed him.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I don't mean any disrespect to him, God rest his soul.
{DIALOGUE}: He was a man of high ideals, so-called, but ideals without common sense can ruin this town.
{META_DATA}: (picking up papers from table)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, you take this loan here to Ernie Bishop... You know, that fellow that sits around all day on his brains in his taxi.
{DIALOGUE}: You know... I happen to know the bank turned down this loan, but he comes here and we're building him a house worth five thousand dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is at the door of the office, holding his coat and papers, ready to leave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I handled that, Mr. Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: You have all the papers there.
{DIALOGUE}: His salary, insurance.
{DIALOGUE}: I can personally vouch for his character.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (sarcastically)
{DIALOGUE}: A friend of yours?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: You see, if you shoot pool with some employee here, you can come and borrow money.
{DIALOGUE}: What does that get us?
{DIALOGUE}: A discontented, lazy rabble instead of a thrifty working class.
{DIALOGUE}: And all because a few starry-eyed dreamers like Peter Bailey stir them up and fill their heads with a lot of impossible ideas.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I say...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George puts down his coat and comes around to the table, incensed by what Potter is saying about his father.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Just a minute – just a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, hold on, Mr. Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: You're right when you say my father was no business man.
{DIALOGUE}: I know that.
{DIALOGUE}: Why he ever started this cheap, penny-ante Building and Loan, I'll never know.
{DIALOGUE}: But neither you nor anybody else can say anything against his character, because his whole life was... Why, in the twenty- five years since he and Uncle Billy started this thing, he never once thought of himself.
{DIALOGUE}: Isn't that right, Uncle Billy?
{DIALOGUE}: He didn't save enough money to send Harry to school, let alone me.
{DIALOGUE}: But he did help a few people get out of your slums, Mr. Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: And what's wrong with that?
{DIALOGUE}: Why... Here, you're all businessmen here.
{DIALOGUE}: Doesn't it make them better citizens?
{DIALOGUE}: Doesn't it make them better customers?
{DIALOGUE}: You... you said... What'd you say just a minute ago?
{DIALOGUE}: ... They had to wait and save their money before they even ought to think of a decent home.
{DIALOGUE}: Wait!
{DIALOGUE}: Wait for what?
{DIALOGUE}: Until their children grow up and leave them?
{DIALOGUE}: Until they're so old and broken- down that they... Do you know how long it takes a working man to save five thousand dollars?
{DIALOGUE}: Just remember this, Mr. Potter, that this rabble you're talking about... they do most of the working and paying and living and dying in this community.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, is it too much to have them work and pay and live and die in a couple of decent rooms and a bath?
{DIALOGUE}: Anyway, my father didn't think so.
{DIALOGUE}: People were human beings to him, but to you, a warped, frustrated old man, they're cattle.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, in my book he died a much richer man than you'll ever be!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not interested in your book.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm talking about the Building and Loan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I know very well what you're talking about.
{DIALOGUE}: You're talking about something you can't get your fingers on, and it's galling you.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what you're talking about, I know.
{META_DATA}: (to the Board)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I've said too much.
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: You're the Board here.
{DIALOGUE}: You do what you want with this thing.
{DIALOGUE}: Just one thing more, though.
{DIALOGUE}: This town needs this measly one-horse institution if only to have some place where people can come without crawling to Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, Uncle Billy!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George leaves the room, followed by the jubilant Uncle Billy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter's face is grim with hatred.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The "frustrated old man" remark was gall in his veins.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Sentimental hogwash!
{DIALOGUE}: I want my motion...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is interrupted by a babble of talk, as the directors take up the argument
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE – BUILDING AND LOAN – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, visibly shaken, is busy with his bag, his papers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is worried about the outcome of the meeting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dissolving the Building and Loan will alter his plans.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy follows him around, chattering.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Boy, oh, boy, that was telling him, George, old boy.
{DIALOGUE}: You shut his big mouth.
{META_DATA}: (to Cousin Tilly and Cousin Eustace)
{DIALOGUE}: You should have heard him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: What happened?
{DIALOGUE}: We heard a lot of yelling.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, we're being voted out of business after twenty-five years.
{DIALOGUE}: Easy come, easy go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{META_DATA}: (reading a newspaper)
{DIALOGUE}: Here it is, "Help Wanted – Female."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – DOORWAY TO OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie is in the doorway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: You still want me to hang around, George?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND THE OTHERS
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (looking at his watch)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, I'll be right down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, you'll miss your train.
{DIALOGUE}: You're a week late for school already.
{DIALOGUE}: Go on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (indicating Board room)
{DIALOGUE}: I wonder what's going on in there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, never mind.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't worry about that.
{DIALOGUE}: They're putting us out of business.
{DIALOGUE}: So what?
{DIALOGUE}: I can get another job.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm only fifty-five.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Fifty-six!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Go on – go on.
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, look, you gave up your boat trip, now you don't want to miss college too, do you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dr. Campbell comes running out, all excited.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: They voted Potter down!
{DIALOGUE}: They want to keep it going!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Eustace, Cousin Tilly and Uncle Billy cheer wildly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dr. Campbell and George shake hands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Whoopee!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: But they've got one condition – only one condition.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What's that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: That's the best part of it.
{DIALOGUE}: They've appointed George here as executive secretary to take his father's place.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no!
{DIALOGUE}: But, Uncle Billy...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: You can keep him on.
{DIALOGUE}: That's all right.
{DIALOGUE}: As secretary you can hire anyone you like.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (emphatically)
{DIALOGUE}: Dr. Campbell, now let's get this thing straight.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm leaving.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm leaving right now.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to school.
{DIALOGUE}: This is my last chance.
{DIALOGUE}: Uncle Billy here, he's your man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. CAMPBELL
{DIALOGUE}: But, George, they'll vote with Potter otherwise.
{META_DATA}: LAP DISSOLVE
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SKY – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same stars we saw in the opening sequence are once more twinkling as we hear the voices form Heaven
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: He didn't go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: That's right.
{DIALOGUE}: Not only that, but he gave his school money to his brother Harry, and sent him to college.
{DIALOGUE}: Harry became a football star – made second team All American.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, but what happened to George?
{META_DATA}: LAP DISSOLVE
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RAILROAD STATION – DAY – FOUR YEARS LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Characteristic activity; a number of people waiting for the train.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy is seated on a baggage wagon eating peanuts as George paces up and down in front of him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: George got four years older, waiting for Harry to come back and take over the Building and Loan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, there are plenty of jobs around for somebody that likes to travel.
{DIALOGUE}: Look at this.
{META_DATA}: (takes some folders from his pocket)
{DIALOGUE}: There... Venezuela oil fields – wanted, man with construction experience.
{DIALOGUE}: Here's the Yukon, right here – wanted, man with engineering experience.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The WHISTLE of the approaching train is heard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Thar she blows.
{DIALOGUE}: You know what the three most exciting sounds in the world are?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh.
{DIALOGUE}: Breakfast is served; lunch is served; dinner...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, no, no, no!
{DIALOGUE}: Anchor chains, plane motors, and train whistles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Peanut?
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TRAIN – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The train comes to a stop, and Harry is among the first to get off, followed by an attractive girl about the same age as he is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George rushes into the shot, and as the brothers embrace:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (joyously)
{DIALOGUE}: There's the professor now!
{DIALOGUE}: Old professor, Phi Beta Kappa Bailey!
{DIALOGUE}: All American!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, if it isn't old George Geographic Explorer Bailey!
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{DIALOGUE}: No husky dogs?
{DIALOGUE}: No sled?
{META_DATA}: (to Uncle Billy)
{DIALOGUE}: Uncle Billy, you haven't changed a bit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Nobody ever changes around here.
{DIALOGUE}: You know that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, am I glad to see you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Say, where's Mother?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: She's home cooking the fatted calf.
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, let's go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, wait.
{DIALOGUE}: Wait... Wait a minute.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The group, including Ruth Dakin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is the young lady who came off the train with Harry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the excitement of greetings she has been momentarily forgotten.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She stands, smiling, waiting.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: How do you do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Ruth Dakin.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTH
{DIALOGUE}: Ruth Dakin Bailey, if you don't mind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Uncle Billy stare, astounded.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I wired you I had a surprise.
{DIALOGUE}: Here she is.
{DIALOGUE}: Meet the wife.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is thunderstruck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes Ruth's hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, what do you know – wife.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, how do you do.
{DIALOGUE}: Congratulations.
{DIALOGUE}: Congratulations.
{DIALOGUE}: What am I doing?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He kisses Ruth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA MOVES WITH them down the platform.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Harry, why didn't you tell somebody?
{META_DATA}: (to Ruth)
{DIALOGUE}: What's a pretty girl like you doing marrying this two-headed brother of mine?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTH
{META_DATA}: (smiling)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'll tell you.
{DIALOGUE}: It's purely mercenary.
{DIALOGUE}: My father offered him a job.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stops, with a sinking feeling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy and Ruth continue out of shot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry stops with George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (as he moves off)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, he gets you and a job?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, Harry's cup runneth over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: George... about that job.
{DIALOGUE}: Ruth spoke out of turn.
{DIALOGUE}: I never said I'd take it.
{DIALOGUE}: You've been holding the bag here for four years, and... well, I won't let you down, George.
{DIALOGUE}: I would like to... Oh, wait a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: I forgot the bags.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be right back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He runs out of the shot, George watching him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George slowly moves after Uncle Billy and Ruth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is thinking deeply.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: It was a surprise to me.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the new Mrs. Bailey, my nephew's wife.
{DIALOGUE}: Old, old friend of the family.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, of course.
{DIALOGUE}: I've heard him speak of you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: And I want to tell you, we're going to give the biggest party this town ever saw.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA MOVES WITH George as he comes into the scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ruth detaches herself from the group and offers George some popcorn.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTH
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Here, have some popcorn.
{DIALOGUE}: George, George, George... that's all Harry ever talks about.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (quietly)
{DIALOGUE}: Ruth, this... what about this job?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTH
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, well, my father owns a glass factory in Buffalo.
{DIALOGUE}: He wants to get Harry started in the research business.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Is it a good job?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTH
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, yes, very.
{DIALOGUE}: Not much money, but a good future, you know.
{DIALOGUE}: Harry's a genius at research.
{DIALOGUE}: My father fell in love with him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: And you did, too?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ruth nods, smiling.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FRONT PORCH – BAILEY HOME – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Eustace is taking a photograph of the family group assembled on the porch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Flash bulbs go off, and the group breaks up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd enters the front door of the house, leaving George and Uncle Billy on the porch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND UNCLE BILLY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The latter is tipsy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He feels very high.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, boy, oh boy, oh boy.
{DIALOGUE}: I feel so good I could spit in Potter's eye.
{DIALOGUE}: I think I will.
{DIALOGUE}: What did you say, huh?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, maybe I'd better go home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks around for his hat, which is on his head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Where's my hat?
{DIALOGUE}: Where's my...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George takes the hat from Uncle Billy's head and hands it to him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, thank you, George.
{DIALOGUE}: Which one is mine?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (laughing)
{DIALOGUE}: The middle one.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, thank you, George, old boy, old boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, look – if you'll point me in the right direction... would you do that?
{DIALOGUE}: George?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Right down here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They descend the porch steps, and George turns his uncle around and heads him down the street.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Old Building and Loan pal, huh...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now you just turn this way and go right straight down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: That way, huh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He staggers out of the scene, and as George turns away, we hear Uncle Billy singing "My Wild Irish Rose."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a CRASH of cans and bottles, then:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm all right.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm all right. "
{DIALOGUE}: ... the sweetest flower that grows... "
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is standing at the garden gate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes some travel folders from his pocket, looks at them and throws them away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is obviously disturbed about the latest turn of events.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His mother comes out of the house and kisses him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Mom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{META_DATA}: (as she kisses him)
{DIALOGUE}: That's for nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: How do you like her?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She nods toward the house, where Harry and Ruth, among a crowd of other couples, are dancing to the MUSIC of a phonograph, and can be seen through the front door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: She's swell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Looks like she can keep Harry on his toes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Keep him out of Bedford Falls, anyway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Did you know that Mary Hatch is back from school?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Came back three days ago.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hmmmm...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Nice girl, Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hmmmm...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Kind that will help you find the answers, George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hmmm...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, stop that grunting.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hmmm...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Can you give me one good reason why you shouldn't call on Mary?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Sure – Sam Wainwright.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Hmmm?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Sam's crazy about Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, she's not crazy about him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, how do you know?
{DIALOGUE}: Did she discuss it with you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well then, how do you know?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I've got eyes, haven't I?
{DIALOGUE}: Why, she lights up like a firefly whenever you're around.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: And besides, Sam Wainwright's away in New York, and you're here in Bedford Falls.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: And all's fair in love and war?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{META_DATA}: (primly)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know about war.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mother, you know, I can see right through you – right back to your back collar button... trying to get rid of me, huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They kiss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Bailey puts George's hat on his head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, here's your hat, what's your hurry?
{DIALOGUE}: All right, Mother, old Building and Loan pal, I think I'll go out and find a girl and do a little passionate necking.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, George!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, if you'll just point me in the right direction... This direction?
{META_DATA}: (as he leaves)
{DIALOGUE}: Good night, Mrs. Bailey.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET BEDFORD FALLS – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is standing in the middle of the street, hands in his pockets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As a girl passes, he turns and watches her for a moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is obviously undecided as to what he wants to do.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. VIOLET BICK'S BEAUTY SHOP – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Violet is locking up for the night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A couple of men are crowding around her, each one bent on taking her out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is laughter, kidding and pawing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks up and sees George standing there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{META_DATA}: (to the two men)
{DIALOGUE}: Excuse me...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Now, wait a minute.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: I think I got a date.
{DIALOGUE}: But stick around, fellows, just in case, huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: We'll wait for you, baby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA PANS WITH Violet as she crosses the street to George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND VIOLET
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Georgie-Porgie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Vi.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks her over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Violet takes her beauty shop seriously and she's an eyeful.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She senses the fact that George is far from immune to her attractions.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She links her arm in his and continues on down the street with him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE MOVING SHOT – GEORGE AND VIOLET
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: What gives?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: Where are you going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I'll probably end up down at the library.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They stop walking and face one another.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: George, don't you ever get tired of just reading about things?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her eyes are seductive and guileful as she looks up at him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is silent for a moment, then blurts out:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes... what are you doing tonight?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{META_DATA}: (feigned surprise)
{DIALOGUE}: Not a thing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Are you game, Vi?
{DIALOGUE}: Let's make a night of it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{META_DATA}: (just what she wanted)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I'd love it, Georgie.
{DIALOGUE}: What'll we do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Let's go out in the fields and take off our shoes and walk through the grass.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: Huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Then we can go up to the falls.
{DIALOGUE}: It's beautiful up there in the moonlight, and there's a green pool up there, and we can swim in it.
{DIALOGUE}: Then we can climb Mt. Bedford, and smell the pines, and watch the sunrise against the peaks, and... we'll stay up there the whole night, and everybody'll be talking and there'll be a terrific scandal...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: George, have you gone crazy?
{DIALOGUE}: Walk in the grass in my bare feet?
{DIALOGUE}: Why, it's ten miles up to Mt. Bedford.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Shhh...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{META_DATA}: (angrily)
{DIALOGUE}: You think just because you...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: By this time a small crowd has collected to watch the above scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Violet is furious and talking in a loud voice, and George is trying to quiet her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, just forget about the whole thing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George stalks off, the crowd breaks into laughter, and we
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RESIDENTIAL STREET – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is walking slowly past the Hatch home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stares meditatively at the simple dwelling, then he starts walking ahead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But after a few steps he turns around and starts back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks past the house a few yards, turns, and starts back again.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BEDROOM WINDOW – HATCH HOME – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is looking out the window, watching George walk back and forth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: What are you doing, picketing?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stops, startled, and looks up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Mary.
{DIALOGUE}: I just happened to be passing by.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, so I noticed.
{DIALOGUE}: Have you made up your mind?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: How's that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Have you made up your mind?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: About what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: About coming in.
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother just phoned and said you were on your way over to pay me a visit.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George looks surprised at this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: My mother just called you?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, how did she know?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Didn't you tell her?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't tell anybody.
{DIALOGUE}: I just went for a walk and happened to be passing by...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Mary has disappeared from the window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: What do you... went for a walk, that's all.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HATCH HOME – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is running down the stairs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (calling off)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be downstairs, mother.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: All right, dear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary looks in a mirror at the bottom of the stairs and fixes her hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is plainly excited at George's visit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She runs into the parlor and puts a sketch on an easel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSERT: THE SKETCH
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a caricature of George throwing a lasso around the moon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lettering on the drawing says: "George Lassos The Moon."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary runs into the hall, opens the phonograph and puts on a record of "Buffalo Gals."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then she opens the front door and stands there waiting for George.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DOORWAY – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is struggling with the gate – he finally kicks it open and starts slowly up the path toward Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, are you coming in or aren't you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'll come in for a minute, but I didn't tell anybody I was coming over here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary and George are in the entrance hall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: When did you get back?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Tuesday.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Where'd you get that dress?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Do you like it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: It's all right.
{DIALOGUE}: I thought you'd go back to New York like Sam and Ingie, and the rest of them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I worked there for a couple of vacations, but I don't know... I guess I was homesick.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (shocked)
{DIALOGUE}: Homesick?
{DIALOGUE}: For Bedford Falls?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, and my family and... oh, everything.
{DIALOGUE}: Would you like to sit down?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They go through the doorway into the parlor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All right, for a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: I still can't understand it though.
{DIALOGUE}: You know I didn't tell anybody I was coming here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Would you rather leave?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, I don't want to be rude.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, then, sit down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George sees the cartoon on the easel and bends down for a close look at it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (indicating cartoon)
{DIALOGUE}: Some joke, huh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary sitting on the divan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is uncomfortable, and she tries desperately to keep the conversation alive.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I see it still smells like pine needles in here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is silence for a moment, then Mary joins in singing with the phonograph record which has been playing all through the above scene:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (singing)
{DIALOGUE}: "And dance by the light..."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, yeah... yeah...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at his watch, as though about to leave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I..
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (desperately)
{DIALOGUE}: It was nice about your brother Harry, and Ruth, wasn't it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh... yeah, yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: That's all right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you like her?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, of course I like her.
{DIALOGUE}: She's a peach.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, it's just marriage in general you're not enthusiastic about, huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, marriage is all right for Harry, and Marty, and Sam and you.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. STAIRS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Hatch, in a bathrobe, and with her hair in curlers, is leaning over the banister as she calls:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PARLOR – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary seated on the divan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Who's down there with you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: It's George Bailey, Mother.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: George Bailey?
{DIALOGUE}: What's he want?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know.
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (indignant)
{DIALOGUE}: Me?
{DIALOGUE}: Not a thing.
{DIALOGUE}: I just came in to get warm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (to mother)
{DIALOGUE}: He's making violent love to me, Mother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is aghast.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: You tell him to go right back home, and don't you leave the house, either.
{DIALOGUE}: Sam Wainwright promised to call you from New York tonight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (heatedly)
{DIALOGUE}: But your mother needn't... you know I didn't come here to... to... to...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (rising)
{DIALOGUE}: What did you come here for?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: You tell me.
{DIALOGUE}: You're supposed to be the one that has all the answers.
{DIALOGUE}: You tell me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (terribly hurt)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, why don't you go home?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (almost shouting)
{DIALOGUE}: That's where I'm going.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know why I came here in the first place!
{DIALOGUE}: Good night!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George leaves the room, the telephone in the hall starts ringing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Good night!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: The telephone!
{DIALOGUE}: It's Sam!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALL – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary comes into the hall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (almost weeping)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll get it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Mary comes into the hall, she stops by the phonograph, which is still playing "Buffalo Gals," takes off the record with a jerk, and smashes it against the machine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The phone is still ringing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH
{DIALOGUE}: Mary, he's waiting!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Mary picks up the phone, George comes in from the front porch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I forgot my hat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (overly enthusiastic)
{DIALOGUE}: Hee-haw!
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Sam, how are you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, great.
{DIALOGUE}: Gee, it's good to hear your voice again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George has stopped, hat in hand, to hear the first greetings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, well, that's awfully sweet of you, Sam.
{DIALOGUE}: (glances toward door, sees George still there) There's an old friend of yours here.
{DIALOGUE}: George Bailey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: You mean old moss-back George?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, old moss-back George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Hee-haw!
{DIALOGUE}: Put him on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Wait a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll call him.
{META_DATA}: (calling)
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. HATCH
{DIALOGUE}: He doesn't want to speak to George, you idiot!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: He does so.
{DIALOGUE}: He asked for him.
{META_DATA}: (calling)
{DIALOGUE}: Geo... George, Sam wants to speak to you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands the instrument to George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Sam.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SAM'S NEW YORK OFFICE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sam is seated at his desk, while a couple of his friends are nearby, with highballs in their hands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{META_DATA}: (into phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, George Baileyoffski!
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, a fine pal you are.
{DIALOGUE}: What're you trying to do?
{DIALOGUE}: Steal my girl?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HATCH HALL – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND MARY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (into phone)
{DIALOGUE}: What do you mean?
{DIALOGUE}: Nobody's trying to steal your girl.
{DIALOGUE}: Here... here's Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: No, wait a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: Wait a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to talk to both of you.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell Mary to get on the extension.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (to Mary)
{DIALOGUE}: Here.
{DIALOGUE}: You take it.
{DIALOGUE}: You tell him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Mother's on the extension.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. UPPER HALLWAY – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – MRS. HATCH
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As she hears this, she hastily hangs up the extension phone on which she has been listening.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO SHOT – GEORGE AND MARY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: We can both hear.
{DIALOGUE}: Come here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary takes the telephone from George and holds it so that of necessity George's cheek is almost against hers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is very conscious of her proximity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: We're listening, Sam.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: I have a big deal coming up that's going to make us all rich.
{DIALOGUE}: George, you remember that night in Martini's bar when you told me you read someplace about making plastics out of soybeans?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Huh?
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah-yeah-yeah... soybeans.
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, Dad's snapped up the idea.
{DIALOGUE}: He's going to build a factory outside of Rochester.
{DIALOGUE}: How do you like that?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is watching George interestedly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is very conscious of her, close to him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Rochester?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, why Rochester?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, why not?
{DIALOGUE}: Can you think of anything better?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I don't know... why not right here?
{DIALOGUE}: You remember that old tool and machinery works?
{DIALOGUE}: You tell your father he can get that for a song.
{DIALOGUE}: And all the labor he wants, too.
{DIALOGUE}: Half the town was thrown out of work when they closed down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: That so?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'll tell him.
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, that sounds great!
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, baby, I knew you'd come through.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, here's the point.
{DIALOGUE}: Mary, Mary, you're in on this too.
{DIALOGUE}: Now listen.
{DIALOGUE}: Have you got any money?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Money?
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah... well, a little.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, now listen.
{DIALOGUE}: I want you to put every cent you've got into our stock, you hear?
{DIALOGUE}: And George, I may have a job for you; that is, unless you're still married to that broken-down Building and Loan.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the biggest thing since radio, and I'm letting you in on the ground floor.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Mary... Mary...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (nervously)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Would you tell that guy I'm giving him the chance of a lifetime, you hear?
{DIALOGUE}: The chance of a lifetime.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Mary listens, she turns to look at George, her lips almost on his lips.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (whispering)
{DIALOGUE}: He says it's the chance of a lifetime.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George can stand it no longer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He drops the phone with a crash, grabs Mary by the shoulders and shakes her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary begins to cry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (fiercely)
{DIALOGUE}: Now you listen to me!
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want any plastics!
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want any ground floors, and I don't want to get married – ever – to anyone!
{DIALOGUE}: You understand that?
{DIALOGUE}: I want to do what I want to do.
{DIALOGUE}: And you're... and you're...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls her to him in a fierce embrace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two meant for each other find themselves in tearful ecstasy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Mary... Mary...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: George... George... George...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Hatch is at the top of the stairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She practically faints at what she sees.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FRONT HALL BAILEY HOME – DAY – SEVERAL MONTHS LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Tilly's face fills the screen as she cries:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Here they come!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA PULLS BACK, and we hear the SOUND of the Wedding March.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: People are crowded into the rooms: family, friends, neighbors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a din of conversation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary and George appear at the top of the stairs in traveling clothes, with Mrs. Hatch, red-eyed, behind them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary throws her bouquet, which is caught by Violet Bick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they come out onto the porch, we see that it is raining.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nevertheless, Cousin Eustace has his camera equipment set up and is taking pictures of the group.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary dodge through the rain and a shower of rice and get into Ernie's taxicab, which pulls away from the curb.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PORCH OF BAILEY HOUSE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Bailey and Annie, the maid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: First Harry, now George.
{DIALOGUE}: Annie, we're just two old maids now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNIE
{DIALOGUE}: You speak for yourself, Mrs. B.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ERNIE'S CAB – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE, MARY AND ERNIE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary are in each other's arms.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: If either of you two see a stranger around here, it's me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, look!
{DIALOGUE}: Somebody's driving this cab.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie reaches over and hands George a bottle of champagne done up in gift wrappings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Bert, the cop, sent this over.
{DIALOGUE}: He said to float away to Happy Land on the bubbles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, look at this.
{DIALOGUE}: Champagne!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Good old Bert.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: By the way, where are you two going on this here now honeymoon?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Where are we going?
{META_DATA}: (takes out a fat roll of bills)
{DIALOGUE}: Look at this.
{DIALOGUE}: There's the kitty, Ernie.
{DIALOGUE}: Here, come on, count it, Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: I feel like a bootlegger's wife.
{META_DATA}: (holding up the money)
{DIALOGUE}: Look!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: You know what we're going to do?
{DIALOGUE}: We're going to shoot the works.
{DIALOGUE}: A whole week in New York.
{DIALOGUE}: A whole week in Bermuda.
{DIALOGUE}: The highest hotels – the oldest champagne – the richest caviar – the hottest music, and the prettiest wife!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: That does it!
{DIALOGUE}: Then what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (to Mary)
{DIALOGUE}: Then what, honey?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: After that, who cares?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: That does it – come here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cab passes the bank, and Ernie sees a crowd of people around the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stops the cab.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scurrying people under umbrellas, swarming around the bank doors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Panic is in the air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Attendants are trying to close down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Several people come running past the cab.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CAB
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE, MARY AND ERNIE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Don't look now, but there's something funny going on over there at the bank, George, I've never really seen one, but that's got all the earmarks of a run.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PASSERBY
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Ernie, if you got any money in the bank, you better hurry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: George, let's not stop.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's go!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George gets out of the cab and looks down the street.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Just a minute, dear.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh-oh...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Please, let's not stop, George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be back in a minute, Mary.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George runs off up the street, toward the Building and Loan.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BUILDING AND LOAN – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – SIDEWALK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An iron grill blocks the street entrance to the Building and Loan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It has been locked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A crowd of men and women are waiting around the grill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are simply-dressed people, to whom their savings are a matter of life and death.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George comes in with an assumed cheerful manner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The people look at him silently, half shamefaced, but grimly determined on their rights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In their hearts there is panic and fear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, everybody.
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Thompson, how are you?
{DIALOGUE}: Charlie?
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter here, can't you get in?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No one answers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He quickly unlocks the grill door and pushes it open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Followed by the crowd, George runs upstairs and into the outer offices of the Building and Loan.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE – BUILDING AND LOAN – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, followed by the still-silent people, comes in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy is standing in the doorway to his private office, taking a drink from a bottle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He motions to George to join him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What is this, Uncle Billy?
{DIALOGUE}: A holiday?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: George...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He points to George's office.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George turns back cheerfully to the crowd.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Come on in, everybody.
{DIALOGUE}: That's right, just come in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George vaults over the counter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now look, why don't you all sit down.
{DIALOGUE}: There are a lot of seats over there.
{DIALOGUE}: Just make yourselves at home.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: George, can I see you a minute?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The people ignore George and remain standing in front of the teller's window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They all have their passbooks out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George hurries into his office where Uncle Billy is waiting for him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND UNCLE BILLY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Why didn't you call me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: I just did, but they said you left.
{DIALOGUE}: This is a pickle, George, this is a pickle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All right now, what happened?
{DIALOGUE}: How did it start?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: How does anything like this ever start?
{DIALOGUE}: All I know is the bank called our loan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: When?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: About an hour ago.
{DIALOGUE}: I had to hand over all our cash.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All of it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Every cent of it, and it still was less than we owe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Holy mackerel!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: And then I got scared, George, and closed the doors.
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: The whole town's gone crazy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The telephone rings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy picks it up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, hello?
{DIALOGUE}: George... it's Potter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S LIBRARY – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter seated behind his desk, his goon alongside him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Standing in front of the desk is a distinguished-looking man, obviously the president of the bank.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is mopping his brow with his handkerchief.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: George, there is a rumor around town that you've closed your doors.
{DIALOGUE}: Is that true?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, well, I'm very glad to hear that... George, are you all right?
{DIALOGUE}: Do you need any police?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND UNCLE BILLY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Police?
{DIALOGUE}: What for?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – POTTER TALKING ON PHONE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Well, mobs get pretty ugly sometimes, you know.
{DIALOGUE}: George, I'm going all out to help in this crisis.
{DIALOGUE}: I've just guaranteed the bank sufficient funds to meet their needs.
{DIALOGUE}: They'll close up for a week, and then reopen.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND UNCLE BILLY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (to Uncle Billy)
{DIALOGUE}: He just took over the bank.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – POTTER ON PHONE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: I may lose a fortune, but I'm willing to guarantee your people too.
{DIALOGUE}: Just tell them to bring their shares over here and I will pay them fifty cents on the dollar.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND UNCLE BILLY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (furiously)
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, you never miss a trick, do you, Potter?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, you're going to miss this one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George bangs the receiver down and turns to meet Uncle Billy's anxious look.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP – POTTER ON PHONE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: If you close your doors before six P.M. you will never reopen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He realizes George has hung up, and clicks the phone furiously.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND UNCLE BILLY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: George, was it a nice wedding?
{DIALOGUE}: Gosh, I wanted to be there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah...
{META_DATA}: (looks at string on Uncle Billy's finger)
{DIALOGUE}: ...you can take this one off now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An ominous SOUND of angry voices comes from the other room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Uncle Billy exit from George's office.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE – BUILDING AND LOAN – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: More people have crowded around the counter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their muttering stops and they stand silent and grim.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is panic in their faces.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, just remember that this thing isn't as black as it appears.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George speaks, sirens are heard passing in the street below.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd turn to the windows, then back to George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I have some news for you, folks.
{DIALOGUE}: I've just talked to old man Potter, and he's guaranteed cash payments at the bank.
{DIALOGUE}: The bank's going to reopen next week.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ED
{DIALOGUE}: But, George, I got my money here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: Did he guarantee this place?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, no, Charlie.
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't even ask him.
{DIALOGUE}: We don't need Potter over here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary and Ernie have come into the room during this scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary stands watching silently.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: I'll take mine now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, but you... you... you're thinking of this place all wrong.
{DIALOGUE}: As if I had the money back in a safe.
{DIALOGUE}: The money's not here.
{DIALOGUE}: Your money's in Joe's house...
{META_DATA}: (to one of the men)
{DIALOGUE}: ...right next to yours.
{DIALOGUE}: And in the Kennedy house, and Mrs. Macklin's house, and a hundred others.
{DIALOGUE}: Why, you're lending them the money to build, and then, they're going to pay it back to you as best they can.
{DIALOGUE}: Now what are you going to do?
{DIALOGUE}: Foreclose on them?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{DIALOGUE}: I got two hundred and forty-two dollars in here, and two hundred and forty-two dollars isn't going to break anybody.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – ANOTHER ANGLE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (handing him a slip)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, Tom.
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: Here you are.
{DIALOGUE}: You sign this.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll get your money in sixty days.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{DIALOGUE}: Sixty days?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, now that's what you agreed to when you bought your shares.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a commotion at the outer doors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A man (Randall) comes in and makes his way up to Tom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RANDALL
{DIALOGUE}: Tom... Tom, did you get your money?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RANDALL
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I did.
{DIALOGUE}: Old man Potter'll pay fifty cents on the dollar for every share you got.
{META_DATA}: (shows bills)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CROWD
{META_DATA}: (ad lib)
{DIALOGUE}: Fifty cents on the dollar!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RANDALL
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, cash!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, what do you say?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, Tom, you have to stick to your original agreement.
{DIALOGUE}: Now give us sixty days on this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{META_DATA}: (turning to Randall)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, Randall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. THOMPSON
{DIALOGUE}: Are you going to go to Potter's?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{DIALOGUE}: Better to get half than nothing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A few other people start for the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA PANS WITH George as he vaults over the counter quickly, speaking to the people.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Tom!
{DIALOGUE}: Tom!
{DIALOGUE}: Randall!
{DIALOGUE}: Now wait... now listen... now listen to me.
{DIALOGUE}: I beg of you not to do this thing.
{DIALOGUE}: If Potter gets hold of this Building and Loan there'll never be another decent house built in this town.
{DIALOGUE}: He's already got charge of the bank.
{DIALOGUE}: He's got the bus line.
{DIALOGUE}: He's got the department stores.
{DIALOGUE}: And now he's after us.
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it's very simple.
{DIALOGUE}: Because we're cutting in on his business, that's why.
{DIALOGUE}: And because he wants to keep you living in his slums and paying the kind of rent he decides.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The people are still trying to get out, but some of them have stood still, listening to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George has begun to make an impression on them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Joe, you lived in one of his houses, didn't you?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, have you forgotten?
{DIALOGUE}: Have you forgotten what he charged you for that broken-down shack?
{META_DATA}: (to Ed)
{DIALOGUE}: Here, Ed.
{DIALOGUE}: You know, you remember last year when things weren't going so well, and you couldn't make your payments.
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't lose your house, did you?
{DIALOGUE}: Do you think Potter would have let you keep it?
{META_DATA}: (turns to address the room again)
{DIALOGUE}: Can't you understand what's happening here?
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you see what's happening?
{DIALOGUE}: Potter isn't selling.
{DIALOGUE}: Potter's buying!
{DIALOGUE}: And why?
{DIALOGUE}: Because we're panicky and he's not.
{DIALOGUE}: That's why.
{DIALOGUE}: He's picking up some bargains.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, we can get through this thing all right.
{DIALOGUE}: We've got to stick together, though.
{DIALOGUE}: We've got to have faith in each other.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. THOMPSON
{DIALOGUE}: But my husband hasn't worked in over a year, and I need money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WOMAN
{DIALOGUE}: How am I going to live until the bank opens?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: I got doctor bills to pay.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: I need cash.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Can't feed my kids on faith.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: During this scene Mary has come up behind the counter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, as the people once more start moving toward the door, she holds up a roll of bills and calls out
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: How much do you need?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George jumps over the counter and takes the money from Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey!
{DIALOGUE}: I got two thousand dollars!
{DIALOGUE}: Here's two thousand dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: This'll tide us over until the bank reopen.
{META_DATA}: (to Tom)
{DIALOGUE}: All right, Tom, how much do you need?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{META_DATA}: (doggedly)
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred and forty-two dollars!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (pleading)
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, Tom, just enough to tide you over till the bank reopens.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{DIALOGUE}: I'll take two hundred and forty-two dollars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George starts rapidly to count out the money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tom throws his passbook on the counter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: There you are.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{DIALOGUE}: That'll close my account.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Your account's still here.
{DIALOGUE}: That's a loan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary turns and slips out through the crowd, followed by Ernie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George hands the two hundred and forty-two dollars to Tom, and speaks to Ed, the next in line.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: All right, Ed?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ED
{DIALOGUE}: I got three hundred dollars here, George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy takes out his wallet and takes out all the cash he's got.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, now, Ed... what'll it take till the bank reopens?
{DIALOGUE}: What do you need?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ED
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I suppose twenty dollars.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: Now you're talking.
{DIALOGUE}: Fine.
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks, Ed.
{META_DATA}: (to Mrs. Thompson, next in line)
{DIALOGUE}: All right, now, Mrs. Thompson.
{DIALOGUE}: How much do you want?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. THOMPSON
{DIALOGUE}: But it's your own money, George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Never mind about that.
{DIALOGUE}: How much do you want?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. THOMPSON
{DIALOGUE}: I can get along with twenty, all right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (counting it out)
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty dollars.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. THOMPSON
{DIALOGUE}: And I'll sign a paper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have to sign anything.
{DIALOGUE}: I know you'll pay it back when you can.
{DIALOGUE}: That's okay.
{META_DATA}: (to woman next in line)
{DIALOGUE}: All right, Mrs. Davis.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DAVIS
{DIALOGUE}: Could I have seventeen-fifty?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Seven...
{META_DATA}: (he kisses her)
{DIALOGUE}: Bless your heart, Of course you can have it.
{DIALOGUE}: You got fifty cents?
{META_DATA}: (counting)
{DIALOGUE}: Seven...
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE BUILDING AND LOAN – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, Uncle Billy and Cousin Tilly are behind the counter, watching the minute hand of a clock on the wall as George counts off the seconds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Eustace is ready to close the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (excitedly)
{DIALOGUE}: We're going to make it, George.
{DIALOGUE}: They'll never close us up today!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (counting)
{DIALOGUE}: Six... five... four... three... two... one... Bingo!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Eustace slams and locks the door, and scurries around the counter to join the others.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: We made it!
{DIALOGUE}: Look...
{META_DATA}: (holds up two bills)
{DIALOGUE}: ... look, we're still in business!
{DIALOGUE}: We've still got two bucks left!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy is taking a drink out of his bottle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, let's have some of that.
{DIALOGUE}: Get some glasses, Cousin Tilly.
{META_DATA}: (to Uncle Billy)
{DIALOGUE}: We're a couple of financial wizards.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Those Rockefellers!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Get a tray for these great big important simoleons.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: We'll save them for seed.
{DIALOGUE}: A toast!
{DIALOGUE}: They raise their glasses.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: A toast!
{DIALOGUE}: A toast to Papa Dollar and to Mama Dollar, and if you want the old Building and Loan to stay in business, you better have a family real quick.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: I wish they were rabbits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I wish they were too.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, let's put them in the safe and see what happens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The four of them parade through the office; George puts the two dollars in the safe.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GROUP AROUND THE SAFE DOOR
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George comes out:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{META_DATA}: (handing out cigars)
{DIALOGUE}: Wedding cigars!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (startled)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh-oh... wedding!
{DIALOGUE}: Holy mackerel, I'm married!
{DIALOGUE}: Where's Mary?
{DIALOGUE}: Mary...
{META_DATA}: (he runs around looking for her)
{DIALOGUE}: Poor Mary.
{DIALOGUE}: Look, I've got a train to catch.
{META_DATA}: (looks at his watch)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, the train's gone.
{DIALOGUE}: I wonder if Ernie's still here with his taxicab?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George rushes into his office to look out the window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{META_DATA}: (on telephone)
{DIALOGUE}: George, there's a call for you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Look, will you get my wife on the phone?
{DIALOGUE}: She's probably over at her mother's.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Bailey is on the phone.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSEUP – GEORGE IS THOROUGHLY RATTLED
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want Mrs. Bailey.
{DIALOGUE}: I want my wife.
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Bailey!
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, that's my wife!
{DIALOGUE}: Here, I'll take it in here.
{META_DATA}: (picks up phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Mary?
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{DIALOGUE}: Listen, dear, I'm sorry... What?
{DIALOGUE}: Come home?
{DIALOGUE}: What home?
{DIALOGUE}: Three-twenty Sycamore?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, what... whose home is that?
{DIALOGUE}: The Waldorf Hotel, huh?
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. OLD GRANVILLE HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An old-fashioned, run-down house, unpainted and warped by the weather.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It once had class but has not been lived in for years.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is the house that George and Mary will live in from now on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The rain is pouring down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A faint glow of light shines out from bottom windows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George hurries into scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stops to make sure it is the right number before going up the steps.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SIDE OF HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert and man working in rain, sorting through travel posters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, this is the company's posters, and the company won't like this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: How would you like to get a ticket next week?
{DIALOGUE}: Haven't you any romance in you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Sure I have, but I got rid of it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{META_DATA}: (reading poster)
{DIALOGUE}: Liver pills!
{DIALOGUE}: Who wants to see liver pills on their honeymoon?
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{DIALOGUE}: They want romantic places, beautiful places... places George wants to go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A sharp whistle is heard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – WINDOW OF HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie is leaning from the window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Bert, here he comes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – BERT AND MAN
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, we got to get this up.
{DIALOGUE}: He's coming.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Who?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: The groom, idiot.
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, get that ladder.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{META_DATA}: (disgustedly)
{DIALOGUE}: What are they – ducks?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – SIDE PORCH OF HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert and the man are putting up travel posters to cover up the broken windows.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Get that ladder up here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: All right – all right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry up... hurry up... hurry up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: I'm hurrying.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is approaching the front door of the house, on which a sign is hanging: "Bridal Suite."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie looks out through the curtain covering the broken glass of the front door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Hiya... Good evening, sir.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie opens the door, revealing himself as a homemade butler.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This has been accomplished by rolling up his pants and putting on an old coachman's hat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George enters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Entray, monsieur, entray.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GRANVILLE HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE ENTERS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The house is carpetless, empty – the rain and wind cause funny noises upstairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A huge fire is burning in the fireplace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Near the fireplace a collection of packing boxes are heaped together in the shape of a small table and covered with a checkered oil cloth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is set for two.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A bucket with ice and a champagne bottle sit on the table as well as a bowl of caviar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two small chickens are impaled on a spit over the fire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A phonograph is playing on a box, and a string from the phonograph is turning the chickens on the spit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The phonograph is playing "Song of the Islands."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is standing near the fireplace looking as pretty as any bride ever looked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is smiling at George, who has been slowly taking in the whole set-up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through a door he sees the end of a cheap bed, over the back of which is a pair of pajamas and a nightie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie exits and closes the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (tears in her eyes)
{DIALOGUE}: Welcome home, Mr. Bailey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (overcome)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'll be... Mary, Mary, where did you...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They rush into each other's arms and hold each other in ecstasy.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SIDE OF HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert and Ernie, standing in the pouring rain, start singing "I Love You Truly."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND MARY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They remain embraced.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Mary...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Remember the night we broke the windows in this old house?
{DIALOGUE}: This is what I wished for.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Darling, you're wonderful.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SIDE OF HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – BERT AND ERNIE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They finish their song, and Ernie kisses Bert on the forehead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert slams Ernie's hat on his head.
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT
{META_DATA}: FADE IN:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SLUM STREET BEDFORD FALLS – DAY – TWO YEARS LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In front of one of the miserable shacks that line the street are two vehicles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of them is George Bailey's rickety car, and the other is an even more rickety truck piled high with household goods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Martini family is moving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The family consists of Martini, his wife and four kid of various ages, from two to ten.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary are helping the Martinis move.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: About a dozen neighbors crowd around.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Martini and George, assisted by three of the Martini children, are carrying out the last of the furniture.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they emerge from the house, one of the neighbors, Schultz, calls out:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCHULTZ
{DIALOGUE}: Martini, you rented a new house?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: Rent?
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: You hear what he say, Mr. Bailey?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What's that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: I own the house.
{DIALOGUE}: Me, Giuseppe Martini.
{DIALOGUE}: I own my own house.
{DIALOGUE}: No more we live like pigs in thisa Potter's Field.
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry, Maria.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARIA
{DIALOGUE}: Yes...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Come on...
{META_DATA}: (to Mary)
{DIALOGUE}: Bring the baby.
{META_DATA}: (to Martini)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll bring the kids in the car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, thank you, Mr. Bailey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary gets in the front seat of the car, with the baby in her arms.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All right, kids – here – get in here.
{DIALOGUE}: Now get right up on the seat there.
{DIALOGUE}: Get the... get the goat!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The family goat gets in the back seat with the three kids.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: Goodbye, everybody!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All in...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The rickety caravan starts off down the street, to the cheers of the neighbors.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BAILEY PARK – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sign hanging from a tree "Welcome to Bailey Park."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA PANS TO follow George's car and the old truck laden with furniture as they pass – we hear Martini's voice singing "O Sole Mio."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bailey Park is a district of new small houses, not all alike, but each individual.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: New lawns here and there, and young trees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It has the promise when built up of being a pleasant little middle class section.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MARTINI'S NEW HOUSE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary are on the porch of the new house, with the Martinis lined up before them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. and Mrs. Martini, welcome home.
{DIALOGUE}: The Martinis cross themselves.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET – BAILEY PARK – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sam Wainwright is standing in front of his big black town car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sam is the epitome of successful, up-and-coming businessman.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His wife, in the car, is a very attractive, sophisticated-looking lady, dripping with furs and jewels.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sam is watching George across the street.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: That old George... he's always making a speech.
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Hee-haw!
{META_DATA}: (wiggles his hands)
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. NEW HOUSE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – MARY AND GEORGE ON PORCH
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (to Mary)
{DIALOGUE}: Sam Wainwright!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, who cares.
{DIALOGUE}: (to Mrs. Martini, giving her loaf of bread) Bread!
{DIALOGUE}: That this house may never know hunger.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Martini crosses herself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (giving her salt)
{DIALOGUE}: Salt!
{DIALOGUE}: That life may always have flavor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (handing bottle to Martini)
{DIALOGUE}: And wine!
{DIALOGUE}: That joy and prosperity may reign forever.
{DIALOGUE}: Enter the Martini castle!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Martinis cross themselves, shaking hands all around.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kids enter, with screams of delight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Martini kisses Mary.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE IN BANK – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter seated in his wheelchair at his desk, with his goon beside him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His rent collector, Reineman, is talking, pointing to maps spread out on the desk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REINEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Look, Mr. Potter, it's no skin off my nose.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just your little rent collector.
{DIALOGUE}: But you can't laugh off this Bailey Park any more.
{DIALOGUE}: Look at it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A buzzer is heard, and Potter snaps on the dictaphone on his desk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SECRETARY'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Congressman Blatz is here to see you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (to dictaphone)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, tell the congressman to wait.
{META_DATA}: (to Reineman)
{DIALOGUE}: Go on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REINEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Fifteen years ago, a half-dozen houses stuck here and there.
{META_DATA}: (indicating map)
{DIALOGUE}: There's the old cemetery, squirrels, buttercups, daisies.
{DIALOGUE}: Used to hunt rabbits there myself.
{DIALOGUE}: Look at it today.
{DIALOGUE}: Dozens of the prettiest little homes you ever saw.
{DIALOGUE}: Ninety per cent owned by suckers who used to pay rent to you.
{DIALOGUE}: Your Potter's Field, my dear Mr. Employer, is becoming just that.
{DIALOGUE}: And are the local yokels making with those David and Goliath wisecracks!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, they are, are they?
{DIALOGUE}: Even though they know the Baileys haven't made a dime out of it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REINEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: You know very well why.
{DIALOGUE}: The Baileys were all chumps.
{DIALOGUE}: Every one of these homes is worth twice what it cost the Building and Loan to build.
{DIALOGUE}: If I were you, Mr. Potter...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, you are not me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REINEMAN
{META_DATA}: (as he leaves)
{DIALOGUE}: As I say, it's no skin off my nose.
{DIALOGUE}: But one of these days this bright young man is going to be asking George Bailey for a job.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reineman exits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: The Bailey family has been a boil on my neck long enough.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He flips the switch on the dictaphone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SECRETARY'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Come in here.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET IN BAILEY PARK – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary are talking to Sam Wainwright in front of the latter's car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hs wife, Jane, is now out of the car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: We just stopped in town to take a look at the new factory, and then we're going to drive on down to Florida.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANE
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you have your friends join us?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: Why, sure.
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, why don't you kids drive down with us, huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I'm afraid I couldn't get away, Sam.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: Still got the nose to the old grindstone, eh?
{DIALOGUE}: Jane, I offered to let George in on the ground floor in plastics, and he turned me down cold.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, now, don't rub it in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not rubbing it in.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I guess we better run along.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is handshaking all around as Sam and Jane get into their car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANE
{DIALOGUE}: Awfully glad to have met you, Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Nice meeting you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Goodbye.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANE
{DIALOGUE}: Goodbye, George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: So long, George.
{DIALOGUE}: See you in the funny papers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Goodbye, Sam.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Have fun.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks for dropping around.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{META_DATA}: (to chauffeur)
{DIALOGUE}: To Florida!
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Hee-haw!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hee-haw.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The big black limousine glides away, leaving George standing with his arm around Mary, gazing broodingly after it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They slowly walk over to George's old car and look at it silently.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter is lighting a big cigar which he has just given George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The goon is beside Potter's chair, as usual.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: Quite a cigar, Mr. Potter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: You like it?
{DIALOGUE}: I'll send you a box.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (nervously)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I..
{DIALOGUE}: I suppose I'll find out sooner or later, but just what exactly did you want to see me about?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (laughs)
{DIALOGUE}: George, now that's just what I like so much about you.
{META_DATA}: (pleasantly and smoothly)
{DIALOGUE}: George, I'm an old man, and most people hate me.
{DIALOGUE}: But I don't like them either, so that makes it all even.
{DIALOGUE}: You know just as well as I do that I run practically everything in this town but the Bailey Building and Loan.
{DIALOGUE}: You know, also, that for a number of years I've been trying to get control of it... or kill it.
{DIALOGUE}: But I haven't been able to do it.
{DIALOGUE}: You have been stopping me.
{DIALOGUE}: In fact, you have beaten me, George, and as anyone in this county can tell you, that takes some doing.
{DIALOGUE}: Take during the depression, for instance.
{DIALOGUE}: You and I were the only ones that kept our heads.
{DIALOGUE}: You saved the Building and Loan, and I saved all the rest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, most people say you stole all the rest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: The envious ones say that, George, the suckers.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I have stated my side very frankly.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, let's look at your side.
{DIALOGUE}: Young man, twenty- seven, twenty-eight... married, making, say... forty a week.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (indignantly)
{DIALOGUE}: Forty-five!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Forty-five.
{DIALOGUE}: Forty-five.
{DIALOGUE}: Out of which, after supporting your mother, and paying your bills, you're able to keep, say, ten, if you skimp.
{DIALOGUE}: A child or two comes along, and you won't even be able to save the ten.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, if this young man of twenty-eight was a common, ordinary yokel, I'd say he was doing fine.
{DIALOGUE}: But George Bailey is not a common, ordinary yokel.
{DIALOGUE}: He's an intelligent, smart, ambitious young man — who hates his job – who hates the Building and Loan almost as much as I do.
{DIALOGUE}: A young man who's been dying to get out on his own ever since he was born.
{DIALOGUE}: A young man... the smartest one of the crowd, mind you, a young man who has to sit by and watch his friends go places, because he's trapped.
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir, trapped into frittering his life away playing nursemaid to a lot of garlic-eaters.
{DIALOGUE}: Do I paint a correct picture, or do I exaggerate?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (mystified)
{DIALOGUE}: Now what's your point, Mr. Potter?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: My point?
{DIALOGUE}: My point is, I want to hire you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (dumbfounded)
{DIALOGUE}: Hire me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: I want you to manage my affairs, run my properties.
{DIALOGUE}: George, I'll start you out at twenty thousand dollars a year.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George drops his cigar on his lap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He nervously brushes off the sparks from his clothes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (flabbergasted)
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty thou... twenty thousand dollars a year?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: You wouldn't mind living in the nicest house in town, buying your wife a lot of fine clothes, a couple of business trips to New York a year, maybe once in a while Europe.
{DIALOGUE}: You wouldn't mind that, would you, George?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Would I?
{META_DATA}: (looking around skeptically)
{DIALOGUE}: You're not talking to somebody else around here, are you?
{DIALOGUE}: You know, this is me, you remember me?
{DIALOGUE}: George Bailey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, yes, George Bailey.
{DIALOGUE}: Whose ship has just come in – providing he has brains enough to climb aboard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, what about the Building and Loan?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, confound it, man, are you afraid of success?
{DIALOGUE}: I'm offering you a three year contract at twenty thousand dollars a year, starting today.
{DIALOGUE}: Is it a deal or isn't it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, Mr. Potter, I..
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: I know I ought to jump at the chance, but I..
{DIALOGUE}: I just... I wonder if it would be possible for you to give me twenty- four hours to think it over?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Sure, sure, sure.
{DIALOGUE}: You go on home and talk about it to your wife.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I'd like to do that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: In the meantime, I'll draw up the papers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All right, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (offers hand)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, George?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (taking his hand)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, Mr. Potter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they shake hands, George feels a physical revulsion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter's hand feels like a cold mackerel to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In that moment of physical contact he knows he could never be associated with this man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George drops his hand with a shudder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He peers intently into Potter's face.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (vehemently)
{DIALOGUE}: No... no... no... no, now wait a minute, here!
{DIALOGUE}: I don't have to talk to anybody!
{DIALOGUE}: I know right now, and the answer is no!
{DIALOGUE}: NO!
{DIALOGUE}: Doggone it!
{META_DATA}: (getting madder all the time)
{DIALOGUE}: You sit around here and you spin your little webs and you think the whole world revolves around you and your money.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it doesn't, Mr. Potter!
{DIALOGUE}: In the... in the whole vast configuration of things, I'd say you were nothing but a scurvy little spider.
{DIALOGUE}: You...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns and shouts at the goon, impassive as ever beside Potter's wheelchair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: ...And that goes for you too!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George opens the office door to exit, he shouts at Mr. Potter's secretary in the outer office
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: And it goes for you too!
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BEDROOM – GEORGE AND MARY'S HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE ENTERS THE BEDROOM
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The room is modestly furnished with just a cheap bed, a chair or two, and a dresser.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is asleep in the bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George comes in, his head is filled with many confusing thoughts, relating to incidents in his past life.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: You wouldn't mind living in the nicest house in town.
{DIALOGUE}: Buying your wife a lot of fine clothes, going to New York on a business trip a couple of times a year.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe to Europe once in a while.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George takes off his hat and coat, moves over to the dresser and stares at his reflection in the mirror.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: I know what I'm going to do tomorrow and the next day and next year and the year after that.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm shaking the dust of this crummy little town off my feet, and I'm going to see the world... And I'm going to build things.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to build air fields.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to build skyscrapers a hundred stories high.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to build a bridge a mile long.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While the above thoughts are passing through George's head, his attention is caught by a picture on the wall near the dresser:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSERT: PICTURE ON THE WALL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is the sketch of George lassoing the moon that we first saw in Mary's living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The lettering reads: "George Lassos The Moon."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: What is it you want, Mary?
{DIALOGUE}: You want the moon?
{DIALOGUE}: If you do, just say the word; I'll throw a lasso around it and pull it down for you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is now awake, and starts singing their theme song:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (singing)
{DIALOGUE}: Buffalo Gals, won't you come out tonight, won't you come out tonight, won't you come out tonight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George crosses over and sits on the edge of the bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary Hatch, why in the world did you ever marry a guy like me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: To keep from being an old maid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: You could have married Sam Wainwright or anybody else in town.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't want to marry anybody else in town.
{DIALOGUE}: I want my baby to look like you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't even have a honeymoon.
{DIALOGUE}: I promised you...
{META_DATA}: (does a double take)
{DIALOGUE}: ...Your what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: My baby.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (incredulously)
{DIALOGUE}: You mean... Mary, you on the nest?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: George Bailey lassos stork.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Lassos the stork!
{DIALOGUE}: You mean you... What is it, a boy or a girl?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary nods her head happily.
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT
{META_DATA}: FADE IN:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MONTAGE SEQUENCE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over the following SERIES OF SHOTS we hear the voices of Joseph and Clarence in Heaven.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET BEDFORD FALLS – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is crossing the street, heading for the offices of the Building and Loan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, you've probably already guessed that George never leaves Bedford Falls.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: No!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – NURSE HOLDING NEWBORN BABY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary had her baby, a boy.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SITTING ROOM – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary sitting on the floor playing with a baby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A little boy is in a playpen nearby.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Then she had another one – a girl.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GRANVILLE HOUSE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOTS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is busy hanging wallpaper and painting the old place.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Day after day she worked away remaking the old Granville house into a home.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GRANVILLE HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George has just come into the hall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is obviously tired and discouraged as he starts up the stairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The knob on the banister comes off in his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Night after night George came back late from the office.
{DIALOGUE}: Potter was bearing down hard.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RECRUITING GROUNDS – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A group of men, obviously just drafted, marching along in a camp.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Then came a war.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. RED CROSS WORKROOM – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Bailey and other women in Red Cross uniforms busily sewing, etc.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Ma Bailey and Mrs. Hatch joined the Red Cross and sewed.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TRAIN IN RAILROAD STATION – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary, with portable U.S.O. pushcart, is serving coffee and doughnuts to men leaning from the train.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary had two more babies, but still found time to run the U.S.O.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FACTORY – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sam Wainwright showing set of blueprints to two Army officers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Sam Wainwright made a fortune in plastic hoods for planes.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FACTORY – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter is wheeled in toward a long table around which several men are seated.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Potter became head of the draft board.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (reading from papers)
{DIALOGUE}: One-A... One-A... One-A...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET IN BEDFORD FALLS – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gower and Uncle Billy are conducting a bond rally from the top of an Army tank.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Gower and Uncle Billy sold war bonds.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BATTLEFIELD – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSEUP
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert, in uniform, moving cautiously with fixed bayonet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Smoke and flashes of gunfire in background.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Bert the cop was wounded in North Africa.
{DIALOGUE}: Got the Silver Star.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SKY – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hundreds of planes, flying overhead, with parachutes dropping from them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Ernie, the taxi driver, parachuted into France.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. REMAGEN BRIDGE OVER THE RHINE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Marty in the foreground, beckoning to soldiers to come on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Marty helped capture the Remagen Bridge.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. READY ROOM ON AIRCRAFT CARRIER – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry is fastening the helmet of his flying clothes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He waves as he exits through the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Harry... Harry Bailey topped them all.
{DIALOGUE}: A Navy flier, he shot down fifteen planes.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. OCEAN FROM DECK OF CARRIER – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A flaming plane crashes into the sea.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: ...two of them as they were about to crash into a transport full of soldiers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, but George...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. RATION OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, behind the counter, is trying to quiet a crowd of people all clamoring for more ration points.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: George?
{DIALOGUE}: Four-F on account of his ear, George fought the battle of Bedford Falls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George shouts.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hold on... hold on... hold on now.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you know there's a war on?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STRET – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, in the uniform of an air raid warden, is patrolling his beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Air raid Warden...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Man beside lighted window pulls down the shade as George blows his whistle.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is helping load his old car with scrap paper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: ...paper drives...
