{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: ...Rubber drives...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CHURCH – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT – PEOPLE PRAYING IN CHURCH
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Like everybody else, on V-E Day he wept and prayed.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CHURCH – ANOTHER ANGLE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – PEOPLE ENTERING CHURCH
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: On V-J Day he wept and prayed again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANKLIN'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Joseph, now show him what happened today.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BEDFORD FALLS STREET – WINTER – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is walking along the sidewalk reading a newspaper.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a raw, gusty day, and his overcoat and muffler flap in the breeze.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Draped around one arm is a large Christmas wreath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Under his other arm are several more copies of the paper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: This morning, day before Christmas, about ten A.M. Bedford Falls time...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George comes to where Ernie, the taxi driver, is standing on the sidewalk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (holding out paper)
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, Ernie, look at that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSERT: NEWSPAPER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The front page of the paper, the Bedford Falls Sentinel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The headline reads: "PRESIDENT DECORATES HARRY BAILEY – LOCAL BOY WINS CONGRESSIONAL MEDAL OF HONOR".
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The subhead tells of a plan for a giant jubilee and parade, to be followed by a banquet, in honor of Commander Harry Bailey, U.S.N. on his way home from Washington after receiving the Congressional Medal of Honor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a large picture of President Truman pinning the coveted medal on Harry's bosom, in the midst of dignitaries; a picture of the transport which Harry saved.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Practically the whole front page is devoted to the story.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND ERNIE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{META_DATA}: (kidding)
{DIALOGUE}: Gonna snow again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (outraged)
{DIALOGUE}: What do you mean – it's gonna snow again?
{DIALOGUE}: Look at the headlines.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: I know – I know – I know.
{DIALOGUE}: I think it's marvelous.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gower comes running across the street from his drugstore and joins them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (reading)
{DIALOGUE}: Commander Harry Bailey.
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Gower, look at this – the second page.
{META_DATA}: (gives them papers)
{DIALOGUE}: Now look, this is for you.
{DIALOGUE}: This is for you, this is for you.
{META_DATA}: (as he leaves)
{DIALOGUE}: See you again.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy is walking along the street, humming happily to himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sees some men decorating the Court House with banners and bunting – there is a huge sign reading: "Welcome Home Harry Bailey"
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (calls out)
{DIALOGUE}: Be sure you spell the name right.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE BUILDING AND LOAN – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FULL SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The offices are unchanged, still small-time and old-fashioned.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same office force, albeit a few years older: Cousin Tilly and Cousin Eustace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seated on a chair is a middle-aged man with a brief case.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The outer door opens and George enters:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Extra!
{DIALOGUE}: Extra!
{DIALOGUE}: Read all about it!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Tilly and Cousin Eustace are talking on the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: It's Harry now on long distance from Washington!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Harry!
{DIALOGUE}: What do you know about that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: He reversed the charges.
{DIALOGUE}: It's okay, isn't it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What do you mean it's okay?
{DIALOGUE}: For a hero?
{META_DATA}: (takes the phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Harry!
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, you old seven kinds of a son of a gun.
{DIALOGUE}: Congratulations!
{DIALOGUE}: How's Mother standing it?
{DIALOGUE}: ... She did?
{DIALOGUE}: What do you know...
{META_DATA}: (to Eustace)
{DIALOGUE}: Mother had lunch with the President's wife!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Wait till Martha hears about this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: What did they have to eat?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: What did they have to eat?
{DIALOGUE}: Harry, you should see what they're cooking up in the town for you... Oh, are they?
{META_DATA}: (to Eustace)
{DIALOGUE}: The Navy's going to fly Mother home this afternoon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: In a plane?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{DIALOGUE}: Uncle Billy?
{META_DATA}: (to Eustace)
{DIALOGUE}: Has Uncle Billy come in yet?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: No, he stopped at the bank first.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: He's not here right now, Harry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Eustace has turned away from George and caught a glimpse of the man waiting in the chair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is Carter, the bank examiner, come for his annual audit of the books of the Building and Loan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: But look...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: George...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: ...now tell me about it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: ...George, that man's here again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What man?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{META_DATA}: (nervously)
{DIALOGUE}: Bank... bank examiner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh...
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Talk to Eustace a minute, will you.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be right back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gives the phone to Eustace, puts down his wreath and goes over to Carter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND CARTER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They shake hands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Good morning, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARTER
{DIALOGUE}: Carter – bank examiner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Carter, Merry Christmas.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARTER
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: We're all excited around here.
{META_DATA}: (shows him paper)
{DIALOGUE}: My brother just got the Congressional Medal of Honor.
{DIALOGUE}: The President just decorated him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARTER
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I guess they do those things.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I trust you had a good year.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Good year?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, between you and me, Mr. Carter, we're broke.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARTER
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, very funny.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well...
{META_DATA}: (leading him into office)
{DIALOGUE}: ...now, come right in here, Mr. Carter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARTER
{META_DATA}: (as they go)
{DIALOGUE}: Although I shouldn't wonder when you okay reverse charges on personal long distance calls.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: George, shall we hang up?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, no.
{DIALOGUE}: He wants to talk to Uncle Billy.
{DIALOGUE}: You just hold on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARTER
{META_DATA}: (in doorway)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, if you'll cooperate, I'd like to finish with you by tonight.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to spend Christmas in Elmira with my family.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't blame you at all, Mr. Carter, Just step right in here.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll fix you up.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BANK – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy is filling out a deposit slip at one of the desks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (writing)
{DIALOGUE}: December twenty-fourth...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes a thick envelope from his inside pocket and thumbs through the bills it contains.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is evidently a large sum of money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Eight thousand...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT – DOOR TO STREET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter is being wheeled in by his goon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Various bank officials run over to greet him – he is reading a newspaper.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy has finished filling out his slip, and comes over to taunt Potter, the envelope containing the money in his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, good morning, Mr. Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: What's the news?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He grabs the paper from Potter's hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY(CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, well, well, Harry Bailey wins Congressional Medal.
{DIALOGUE}: That couldn't be one of the Bailey boys?
{DIALOGUE}: You just can't keep those Baileys down, now, can you, Mr. Potter?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: How does slacker George feel about that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Very jealous, very jealous.
{DIALOGUE}: He only lost three buttons off his vest.
{DIALOGUE}: Of course, slacker George would have gotten two of those medals if he had gone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Bad ear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy folds Potter's paper over the envelope containing his money, and flings his final taunt at the old man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: After all, Potter, some people like George had to stay home.
{DIALOGUE}: Not every heel was in Germany and Japan!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In a cold rage, Potter grabs his paper and wheels off toward his office.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy smiles triumphantly and goes toward deposit window with his deposit slip.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLOSE SHOT
{DIALOGUE}: Uncle Billy and bank teller at the window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (still chuckling)
{DIALOGUE}: Good morning, Horace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy hands the bank book over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The teller opens it, starts to punch it with rubber stamps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER
{DIALOGUE}: I guess you forgot something.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER
{DIALOGUE}: You forgot something.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER
{DIALOGUE}: Well, aren't you going to make a deposit?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Sure, sure I am.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER
{DIALOGUE}: Well, then... it's usually customary to bring the money with you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, shucks...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy searches through every pocket he has.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (looks bewildered)
{DIALOGUE}: I know I had...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The teller, knowing the old man's vagaries, points to one of the numerous string tied around his fingers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER
{DIALOGUE}: How about that one there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Hmm?
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I..
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter is now behind his desk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He spreads the newspaper out in front of him, muttering as he does so.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Bailey...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sees the envelope, looks inside at the money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, to his goon, indicating the office door:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Take me back there.
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry up.
{META_DATA}: (as they go)
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, look sharp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter opens the door just a little, and peers through into the bank.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BANK – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – DEPOSIT SLIP DESK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy looks around for the money envelope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is not there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks puzzled, thinks hard, then a look of concern creeps into his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts thumping his pockets, with increasing panic, and looks in the waste paper basket on the floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finally rushes through the door and out into the street.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – POTTER WATCHING THROUGH THE DOOR
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (to goon)
{DIALOGUE}: Take me back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The goon wheels him back to his desk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is deep in thought, with a crafty expression on his face.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy running across the street in the direction of the Building and Loan.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE – BUILDING AND LOAN – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George coming from room where he has just left the bank examiner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Just make yourself at home, Mr. Carter.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll get those books for you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sees Violet Bick standing there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, hello, Vi.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: George, can I see you for a second?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Why, of course you can.
{DIALOGUE}: Come on in the office here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hears a noise, and sees Uncle Billy entering the office.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Uncle Billy, talk to Harry.
{DIALOGUE}: He's on the telephone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Violet enter his private office.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy comes hurrying in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry, Uncle Billy, hurry.
{DIALOGUE}: Long distance, Washington.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, here's Harry on the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Harry, your nephew, remember?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Here he is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy picks up the phone and speaks distractedly, without knowing what he is saying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello... hello... Yes, Harry – yes... everything... everything's fine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hangs up agitatedly, muttering to himself as he goes into his own office.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Tilly and Cousin Eustace look after him, dumbfounded.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: I should have my head examined.
{DIALOGUE}: Eight thousand dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: It's got to be somewhere.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND VIOLET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George has just finished writing something, and is slipping the paper into an envelope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (hands it to her)
{DIALOGUE}: Here you are.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{META_DATA}: (bitterly)
{DIALOGUE}: Character?
{DIALOGUE}: If I had any character, I'd...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: It takes a lot of character to leave your home town and start all over again.
{DIALOGUE}: He pulls some money from his pocket, and offers it to her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: No, George, don't...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Here, now, you're broke, aren't you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: I know, but...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want to do, hock your furs, and that hat?
{DIALOGUE}: Want to walk to New York?
{DIALOGUE}: You know, they charge for meals and rent up there just the same as they do in Bedford Falls.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{META_DATA}: (taking money)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah – sure...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: It's a loan.
{DIALOGUE}: That's my business.
{DIALOGUE}: Building and Loan.
{DIALOGUE}: Besides, you'll get a job.
{DIALOGUE}: Good luck to you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks at him, then says a strange thing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: I'm glad I know you, George Bailey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She reaches up and kisses him on the cheek, leaving lipstick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George opens the door for her.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George and Violet come through the door, they are being watched by Cousin Tilly, Cousin Eustace and the bank examiner, who is still waiting to go to work on the books.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Say hello to New York for me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah – yeah... sure I will.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, let's hear from you...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Violet sees the lipstick on George's cheek, and dabs at it with her handkerchief.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter?
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas, Vi.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas, George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She exits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MR. CARTER
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Bailey...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Mr. Carter, I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be right with you.
{META_DATA}: (to Cousin Tilly)
{DIALOGUE}: Uncle Billy in?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN TILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, he's in his office.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DOORWAY TO UNCLE BILLY'S OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George opens the door he sees Uncle Billy frantically looking for the missing envelope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The office is in a mess, drawers are opened, and papers scattered on the floor and on the desk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Unc... What's going on?
{DIALOGUE}: The bank examiner's here, and I..
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (in dismay)
{DIALOGUE}: He's here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: He wants the accounts payable...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stops short, suddenly aware of the tragic old eyes looking up at him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter with you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy gestures nervously for George to come in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He does so and closes the door.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OUTER OFFICE – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Tilly is at her switchboard, and Cousin Eustace standing beside her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carter is still waiting in the doorway to his office.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly the door opens and George comes striding out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes directly to the safe and starts searching, but doesn't find the money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then he goes to the cash drawer in the counter, and looks through it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Eustace...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Come here a minute.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cousin Eustace runs over to George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Did you see Uncle Billy with any cash last night?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUSIN EUSTACE
{DIALOGUE}: He had it on his desk counting it before he closed up.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET BEDFORD FALLS – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy and George are retracing the former's steps through the snow, looking everywhere for the missing money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They pause for a moment on the sidewalk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now look, did you buy anything?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: Not even a stick of gum.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: Now we'll go over every step you took since you left the house.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: This way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They continue on down the street on their search.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WINDOW OF POTTER'S OFFICE IN BANK – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter is peering through the slats of the Venetian blind, watching them as they go.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET BEDFORD FALLS – DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MOVING SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Uncle Billy continue their search.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. UNCLE BILLY'S LIVING ROOM
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A shabby, old-fashioned, gas-lit room which has been turned almost inside out and upside down in an effort to locate the missing money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Drawers of an old secretary have been pulled out and are on the floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Every conceivable place which might have been used by Uncle Billy to put the money has been searched.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, his hair rumpled, is feverishly pursuing the search.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy is seated behind the desk, his head on his hands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: And did you put the envelope in your pocket?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah... yeah... maybe... maybe...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (shouts)
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe – maybe!
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want any maybe.
{DIALOGUE}: Uncle Billy, we've got to find that money!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (piteously)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm no good to you, George.
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Listen to me.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have any secret hiding place here in the house?
{DIALOGUE}: Someplace you could have put it?
{DIALOGUE}: Someplace to hide the money?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (exhausted)
{DIALOGUE}: I've been over the whole house, even in rooms that have been locked ever since I lost Laura.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy starts sobbing hysterically.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George grabs him by the lapels and shakes him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (harshly)
{DIALOGUE}: Listen to me!
{DIALOGUE}: Listen to me!
{DIALOGUE}: Think!
{DIALOGUE}: Think!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (sobbing)
{DIALOGUE}: I can't think any more, George.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't think any more.
{DIALOGUE}: It hurts...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George jerks him to his feet and shakes him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy stands before him like a frisked criminal, all his pockets hanging out, empty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George's eyes and manner are almost maniacal.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (screaming at him)
{DIALOGUE}: Where's that money, you stupid, silly old fool?
{DIALOGUE}: Where's the money?
{DIALOGUE}: Do you realize what this means?
{DIALOGUE}: It means bankruptcy and scandal, and prison!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He throws Uncle Billy down into his chair, and still shouts at him:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: That's what it means!
{DIALOGUE}: One of us is going to jail!
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it's not going to be me!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George turns and heads for the door, kicking viciously at a waste basket on the floor as he goes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy remains sobbing at the table, his head in his arms.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGE'S LIVING ROOM – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Janie (aged eight) is seated at the piano playing "Hark, the Herald Angels Sing," which she practices during the remainder of this scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a Christmas tree all decorated near the fireplace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At a large table Mary is busy putting cellophane bows and decorations on gift packages.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At a small table Pete (aged nine) is seated with pad and pencil in the throes of composition.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On the floor Tommy (aged three) is playing with a toy vacuum cleaner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear the SOUND of a door open and close.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary turns and sees George enter the hall, a slight powdering of snow on his head and shoulders.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALL – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As George comes into the house.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Hello darling.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHILDREN
{DIALOGUE}: Hello Daddy, hello daddy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (indicating tree)
{DIALOGUE}: How do you like it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George sneezes violently.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY AND CHILDREN
{DIALOGUE}: Bless you!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Did you bring the wreath?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Did you bring the Christmas wreath?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{DIALOGUE}: What wreath?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: The Merry Christmas wreath for the window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (gruffly)
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I left it at the office.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Is it snowing?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, just started.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Where's your coat and hat?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Left them at the office.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary stares at him, aware that something unusual has happened.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (bitterly)
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing's the matter.
{DIALOGUE}: Everything's all right.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LIVING ROOM – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George slumps into an armchair and lifts Tommy onto his lap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is helping Pete decorate the Christmas tree.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Go on, Pete, you're a big boy.
{DIALOGUE}: You can put the star up.
{DIALOGUE}: Way up at the top.
{DIALOGUE}: That's it.
{DIALOGUE}: Fill in that little bare spot right there.
{DIALOGUE}: That's it.
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Isn't it wonderful about Harry?
{DIALOGUE}: We're famous, George.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll bet I had fifty calls today about the parade, the banquet.
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother's so excited, she...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: During this scene, George has been sitting in the chair, hugging Tommy to him, and crying quietly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary realizes that something is seriously wrong, and breaks off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Janie is thumping away at the piano.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Must she keep playing that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANIE
{META_DATA}: (hurt)
{DIALOGUE}: I have to practice for the party tonight, Daddy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Mommy says we can stay up till midnight and sing Christmas carols.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOMMY
{DIALOGUE}: Can you sing, Daddy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Better hurry and shave.
{DIALOGUE}: The families will be here soon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (rising from chair)
{DIALOGUE}: Families!
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want the families over here!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary leads him out toward the kitchen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Come on out in the kitchen with me while I finish dinner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They exit with Tommy hanging onto George's coat-tails, and pulling at him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA PANS WITH them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOMMY
{DIALOGUE}: Excuse me... excuse me...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALL – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they go toward kitchen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Have a hectic day?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (bitterly)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, yeah, another big red letter day for the Baileys.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Daddy, the Browns next door have a new car.
{DIALOGUE}: You should see it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (turns on him)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, what's the matter with our car?
{DIALOGUE}: Isn't it good enough for you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, Daddy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOMMY
{META_DATA}: (tugging at coat)
{DIALOGUE}: Excuse me, excuse me...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. KITCHEN – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They come through the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (annoyed)
{DIALOGUE}: Excuse you for what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOMMY
{DIALOGUE}: I burped!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: All right, darling, you're excused.
{DIALOGUE}: Now go upstairs and see what little Zuzu wants.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tommy leaves, and Mary turns to the stove.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Zuzu!
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter with Zuzu?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, she's got a cold.
{DIALOGUE}: She's in bed.
{DIALOGUE}: Caught it coming home from school.
{DIALOGUE}: They gave her a flower for a prize and she didn't want to crush it so she didn't button up her coat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What is it, a sore throat or what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Just a cold.
{DIALOGUE}: The doctor says it's nothing serious.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: The doctor?
{DIALOGUE}: Was the doctor here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, I called him right away.
{DIALOGUE}: He says it's nothing to worry about.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Is she running a temperature?
{DIALOGUE}: What is it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Just a teensie one – ninety-nine, six.
{DIALOGUE}: She'll be all right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George paces about the kitchen, worried.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Gosh, it's this old house.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know why we don't all have pneumonia.
{DIALOGUE}: This drafty old barn!
{DIALOGUE}: Might as well be living in a refrigerator.
{DIALOGUE}: Why did we have to live here in the first place and stay around this measly, crummy old town?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (worried)
{DIALOGUE}: George, what's wrong?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Wrong?
{DIALOGUE}: Everything's wrong!
{DIALOGUE}: You call this a happy family?
{DIALOGUE}: Why did we have to have all these kids?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{META_DATA}: (coming in)
{DIALOGUE}: Dad, how do you spell "frankincense"?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (shouts)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: Ask your mother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George goes toward doorway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Where're you going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Going up to see Zuzu.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear his footsteps as he leaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary looks after him, puzzled and concerned, then comes over to Pete.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: He told me to write a play for tonight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: F-R-A-N-K-I-N...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALL – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE STARTS UP THE STAIRS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The knob on the banister comes off in his hand, and for a moment he has an impulse to hurl it into the living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, he replaces the knob, and goes on up the stairs.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ZUZU'S BEDROOM – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FULL SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The SOUND of Janie at the piano can be heard, the same monotonous rhythm over and over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Zuzu (aged six) is sitting up in her bed, the lamp burning beside her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is holding her prize flower.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George tiptoes in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, as he sees she's awake, he comes over, sitting on the edge of her bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, Daddy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, what happened to you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: I won a flower.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She starts to get out of bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Wait now.
{DIALOGUE}: Where do you think you're going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: Want to give my flower a drink.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All right, all right.
{DIALOGUE}: Here, give Daddy the flower.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll give it a drink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She shakes her head and presses the flower to her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A few petals fall off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She picks them up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: Look, Daddy... paste it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, all right.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I'll paste this together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands him the fallen petals and the flower.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns his back to Zuzu, pretending to be tinkering with the flower.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sticks the fallen petals in his watch pocket, rearranges the flower, and then turns back to Zuzu.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: There it is, good as new.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: Give the flower a drink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George puts the flower in a glass of water on the table beside her bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, will you do something for me?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP – GEORGE AND ZUZU
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They whisper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Will you try to get some sleep?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not sleepy.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to look at my flower.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I know – I know, but you just go to sleep, and then you can dream about it, and it'll be a whole garden.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: It will?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She closes her eyes and relaxes on the bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George pulls the covers over her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He bends down and his lips touch a tendril of the child's hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then he gets up and tiptoes out of the room.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LIVING ROOM – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Janie is still pounding with grim determination at the piano.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pete is seated at the table writing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tommy is playing with his toy vacuum cleaner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The telephone rings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANIE AND PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Telephone.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LIVING ROOM – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary comes in and picks up the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: I'll get it.
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, this is Mrs. Bailey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George enters shot, and stands listening to her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, thank you, Mrs. Welch.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sure she'll be all right.
{DIALOGUE}: The doctor says that she ought to be out of bed in time to have her Christmas dinner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Is that Zuzu's teacher?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (hand over receiver)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Let me speak to her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He snatches the phone from Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Mrs. Welch?
{DIALOGUE}: This is George Bailey.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm Zuzu's father.
{DIALOGUE}: Say, what kind of a teacher are you anyway?
{DIALOGUE}: What do you mean sending her home like that, halfnaked?
{DIALOGUE}: Do you realize she'll probably end up with pneumonia on account of you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (shocked)
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She puts a restraining hand on his arm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shakes it off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She cannot know that George's tirade against Mrs. Welch is really a tirade against the world, against life itself, against God.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over the phone we hear Mrs. Welch's voice sputtering with protest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Is this the sort of thing we pay taxes for – to have teachers like you?
{DIALOGUE}: Silly, stupid, careless people who send our kids home without any clothes on?
{DIALOGUE}: You know, maybe my kids aren't the best-dressed kids; maybe they don't have any decent clothes...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary succeeds in wresting the phone from George's hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, that stupid...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary speaks quickly in to the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Mrs. Welch.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to apologize... hello... hello...
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: She's hung up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (savagely)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll hang her up!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the telephone is suddenly alive with a powerful male voice calling:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MR. WELCH'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, who do you think you are?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George hears this and grabs the receiver from Mary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (to Mary)
{DIALOGUE}: Wait a minute.
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello?
{DIALOGUE}: Who is this?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Mr. Welch?
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, that's fine, Mr. Welch.
{DIALOGUE}: Gives me a chance to tell you what I really think of your wife.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary once more tries to take the phone from him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: George...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (raving at her)
{DIALOGUE}: Will you get out and let me handle this?
{META_DATA}: (into phone – shouting)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello?
{DIALOGUE}: Hello?
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, you will, huh?
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, Mr. Welch, any time you think you're man enough... Hello?
{DIALOGUE}: Any...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But before he can think of an insult to top Welch's, we hear a click on the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hangs up the receiver, and turns toward the living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His face is flushed and wet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Daddy, how do you spell "Hallelujah"?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (shouts)
{DIALOGUE}: How should I know?
{DIALOGUE}: What do you think I am, a dictionary?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He yells at Tommy, noisily playing with his vacuum cleaner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Tommy, stop that!
{DIALOGUE}: Stop it!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Janie is still practicing at the piano, monotonously.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (savagely)
{DIALOGUE}: Janie, haven't you learned that silly tune yet?
{DIALOGUE}: You've played it over and over again.
{DIALOGUE}: Now stop it!
{DIALOGUE}: Stop it!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LIVING ROOM – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The room has suddenly become ominously quiet, the only SOUND being George's labored breathing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George goes over to a corner of the room where his workshop is set up – a drawing table, several models of modern buildings, bridges, etc.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Savagely he kicks over the models, picks up some books and hurls them into the corner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary and the children watch, horrified.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George looks around and sees them staring at him as if he were some unknown wild animal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The three children are crying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (gasping for breath)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry, Mary, Janie.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't mean... you go on and practice.
{DIALOGUE}: Pete, I owe you an apology, too.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want to know?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{META_DATA}: (holding back his tears)
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing, Daddy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary and the children stare at him, stunned by his furious outburst.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is silence in the room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter with everybody?
{DIALOGUE}: Janie, go on.
{DIALOGUE}: I told you to practice.
{META_DATA}: (shouts)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, go on, play!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Janie breaks into sobs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANIE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Daddy...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (in an outburst)
{DIALOGUE}: George, why must you torture the children?
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sight of Mary and the children suffering is too much for George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks around him, then quickly goes out the front door of the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary goes to the phone, picks it up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Bedford, two-four-seven, please.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Is Daddy in trouble?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANIE
{DIALOGUE}: Shall I pray for him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, Janie, pray very hard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOMMY
{DIALOGUE}: Me, too?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: You too, Tommy.
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Uncle Billy?
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POTTER'S OFFICE IN BANK – NIGHT – 8:00 P.M.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSEUP
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Potter is seated at his desk, his goon beside him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is signing some papers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is seated in a chair before the desk, without a hat or coat, covered lightly with snow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm in trouble, Mr. Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: I need help.
{DIALOGUE}: Through some sort of an accident my company's short in their accounts.
{DIALOGUE}: The bank examiner's up there today.
{DIALOGUE}: I've got to raise eight thousand dollars immediately.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (casually)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, so that's what the reporters wanted to talk to you about?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (incredulous)
{DIALOGUE}: The reporters?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: They called me up from your Building and Loan.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, there's a man over there from the D.A.'s office, too.
{DIALOGUE}: He's looking for you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (desperate)
{DIALOGUE}: Please help me, Mr. Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: Help me, won't you please?
{DIALOGUE}: Can't you see what it means to my family?
{DIALOGUE}: I'll pay you any sort of a bonus on the loan... any interest.
{DIALOGUE}: If you still want the Building and Loan, why I..
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: George, could it possibly be there's a slight discrepancy in the books?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: There's nothing wrong with the books.
{DIALOGUE}: I've just misplaced eight thousand dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't find it anywhere.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (looking up)
{DIALOGUE}: You misplaced eight thousand dollars?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Have you notified the police?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't want the publicity.
{DIALOGUE}: Harry's homecoming tomorrow...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (snorts)
{DIALOGUE}: They're going to believe that one.
{DIALOGUE}: What've you been doing, George?
{DIALOGUE}: Playing the market with the company's money?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: I haven't.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: What is it – a woman, then?
{DIALOGUE}: You know, it's all over town that you've been giving money to Violet Bick.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (incredulous)
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Not that it makes any difference to me, but why did you come to me?
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you go to Sam Wainwright and ask him for the money?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I can't get hold of him.
{DIALOGUE}: He's in Europe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Well, what about all your other friends?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: They don't have that kind of money, Mr. Potter.
{DIALOGUE}: You know that.
{DIALOGUE}: You're the only one in town that can help me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: I see.
{DIALOGUE}: I've suddenly become quite important.
{DIALOGUE}: What kind of security would I have, George?
{DIALOGUE}: Have you got any stocks?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (shaking his head)
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Bonds?
{DIALOGUE}: Real estate?
{DIALOGUE}: Collateral of any kind?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (pulls out policy)
{DIALOGUE}: I have some life insurance, a fifteen thousand dollar policy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: Yes... how much is your equity in it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Five hundred dollars.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (sarcastically)
{DIALOGUE}: Look at you.
{DIALOGUE}: You used to be so cocky!
{DIALOGUE}: You were going to go out and conquer the world!
{DIALOGUE}: You once called me a warped, frustrated old man.
{DIALOGUE}: What are you but a warped, frustrated young man?
{DIALOGUE}: A miserable little clerk crawling in here on your hands and knees and begging for help.
{DIALOGUE}: No securities – no stocks – no bonds – nothing but a miserable little five hundred dollar equity in a life insurance policy.
{DIALOGUE}: You're worth more dead than alive.
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you go to the riff-raff you love so much and ask them to let you have eight thousand dollar?
{DIALOGUE}: You know why?
{DIALOGUE}: Because they'd run you out of town on a rail... But I'll tell you what I'm going to do for you, George.
{DIALOGUE}: Since the state examiner is still here, as a stockholder of the Building and Loan, I'm going to swear out a warrant for your arrest.
{DIALOGUE}: Misappropriation of funds – manipulation – malfeasance...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George turns and starts out of the office as Potter picks up the phone and dials.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{DIALOGUE}: All right, George, go ahead.
{DIALOGUE}: You can't hide in a little town like this.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is out of the door by now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA MOVES CLOSER to Potter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POTTER
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Bill?
{DIALOGUE}: This is Potter.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET BEDFORD FALLS – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George comes out of the bank into the falling snow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He crosses the street, tugs at the door of his old car, finally steps over the door, and drives off.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MARTINI'S BAR – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An attractive little roadside tavern, with the name "Martini's" in neon lights on the front wall.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MARTINI'S BAR – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The place is an Italian restaurant with bar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bottles sparkle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are Christmas greens and holly decorating the place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It has a warm, welcoming spirit, like Martini himself, who is welcoming new arrivals.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The booths and the checkered-cloth-covered tables are full.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is an air of festivity and friendliness, and more like a party than a public drinking place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is seated at the bar – he has had a great deal to drink, far more than he's accustomed to.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI'S VOICE
{META_DATA}: (greeting new customers)
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas.
{DIALOGUE}: Glad you came.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: How about some of that good spaghetti?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: We got everything.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: During this, CAMERA MOVES CLOSER to George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nick, the bartender, is watching him solicitously.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seated on the other side of George is a burly individual, drinking a glass of beer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is mumbling:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: God... God... Dear Father in Heaven, I'm not a praying man, but if you're up there and you can hear me, show me the way.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm at the end of my rope.
{DIALOGUE}: Show me the way, God.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICK
{META_DATA}: (friendly)
{DIALOGUE}: Are you all right, George?
{DIALOGUE}: Want someone to take you home?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George shakes his head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Martini comes over to his side.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{META_DATA}: (worried)
{DIALOGUE}: Why you drink so much, my friend?
{DIALOGUE}: Please go home, Mr. Bailey.
{DIALOGUE}: This is Christmas Eve.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The ugly man next to George, who has been listening, reacts sharply to the name "Bailey."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Bailey?
{DIALOGUE}: Which Bailey?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICK
{DIALOGUE}: This is Mr. George Bailey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Without any warning, the burly man throws a vicious punch at George, who goes down and out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Martini, Nick and several others rush to pick him up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: And the next time you talk to my wife like that you'll get worse.
{DIALOGUE}: She cried for an hour.
{DIALOGUE}: It isn't enough she slaves teaching your stupid kids how to read and write, and you have to bawl her out...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{META_DATA}: (furious)
{DIALOGUE}: You get out of here, Mr. Welch!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Welch reaches in his pocket for money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WELCH
{DIALOGUE}: Now wait... I want to pay for my drink.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: Never mind the money.
{DIALOGUE}: You get out of here quick.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WELCH
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: You hit my best friend.
{DIALOGUE}: Get out!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nick and Martini shove Welch out the door, then run back to help George to his feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George's mouth is cut and bleeding.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICK
{DIALOGUE}: You all right, George?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (stunned)
{DIALOGUE}: Who was that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: He's gone.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't worry.
{DIALOGUE}: His name is Welch.
{DIALOGUE}: He don't come in to my place no more.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh – Welch.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what I get for praying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: The last time he come in here.
{DIALOGUE}: You hear that, Nick?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICK
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, you bet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Where's my insurance policy?
{META_DATA}: (finds it in pocket)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, here...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts for the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no, Please, don't go out this way, Mr. Bailey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm all right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nick and Martini try to stop him, but he shrugs them off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no – you don't feel so good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm all right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: Please don't go away – please!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George opens the door and exits to the street.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RESIDENTIAL STREET – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George's car comes along the empty street, through the falling snow, suddenly swerves and crashes into a tree near the sidewalk of a house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George gets out to look at the damage, and savagely kicks at the open door of the car, trying to shut it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The noise brings the owner of the house running out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OWNER
{DIALOGUE}: What do you think you're doing?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stands unsteadily near the car, shaken by the accident.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The front lights are broken and the fender is ripped.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stands dully looking at the damage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The owner comes up, looking at his tree.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans over to examine the damages.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OWNER
{META_DATA}: (with indignation)
{DIALOGUE}: Now look what you did.
{DIALOGUE}: My greatgrandfather planted this tree.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George staggers off down the street, paying no attention to the man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OWNER
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, you... Hey, you!
{DIALOGUE}: Come back here, you drunken fool!
{DIALOGUE}: Get this car out of here!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BRIDGE OVER RIVER – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is crossing the approach to the bridge when a truck swings around the corner and nearly hits him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, what's the matter with you?
{DIALOGUE}: Look where you're going!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The truck turns onto the bridge, and George takes a narrow catwalk at the railing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George has stopped by the railing at the center of the bridge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The snow is now falling hard.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RIVER – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA SHOOTING DOWN from George's angle TO the water, dotted with floating ice, passing under the bridge.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BRIDGE AT RAILING – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP – GEORGE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stares down at the water, desperate, trying to make up his mind to act.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans over looking at the water, fascinated, glances furtively around him, hunches himself as though about to jump.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From above George a body hurtles past and lands in the water with a loud splash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George looks down, horrified.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VOICE
{META_DATA}: (from river)
{DIALOGUE}: Help!
{DIALOGUE}: Help!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George quickly takes off his coat and dives over the railing into the water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSER ANGLE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George comes up, sees the man flailing about in the water, and CAMERA PANS WITH him as he swims toward the man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Help!
{DIALOGUE}: Help!
{DIALOGUE}: Help!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TOLL HOUSE ON BRIDGE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The toll house keeper, hearing the cries for help, comes running out on the bridge with a flashlight, which he shines on the two figures struggling in the water below.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RIVER – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The man in the water is Clarence, the angel whose voice we have heard speaking from Heaven.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George reaches him, grabs hold of him, and starts swimming for shore.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TOLL HOUSE ON BRIDGE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT – GEORGE, CLARENCE, AND THE TOLLKEEPER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is seated before a wood-burning stove before which his clothes are drying on a line.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is in his long winter underwear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is sipping a mug of hot coffee, staring at the stove, cold, gloomy and drunk, ignoring Clarence and the tollkeeper, preoccupied by his near suicide and his unsolved problems.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence is standing on the other side of the stove, putting on his undershirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is a ludicrous seventeenth century garment which looks like a baby's night shirt – with embroidered cuffs and collar, and gathered at the neck with a drawstring.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It falls below his knees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tollkeeper is seated against the wall eyeing them suspiciously.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Throughout the scene he attempts to spit, but each time is stopped by some amazing thing Clarence does or says.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence becomes aware that his garment is amazing the tollkeeper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't have time to get some stylish underwear.
{DIALOGUE}: My wife gave me this on my last birthday.
{DIALOGUE}: I passed away in it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tollkeeper, about to spit, is stopped in the middle of it by this remark.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence, secretly trying to get George's attention, now picks up a copy of "Tom Sawyer" which is hanging on the line, drying.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shakes the book.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Tom Sawyer's drying out, too.
{DIALOGUE}: You should read the new book Mark Twain's writing now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tollkeeper stares at him incredulously.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOLLKEEPER
{DIALOGUE}: How'd you happen to fall in?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't fall in.
{DIALOGUE}: I jumped in to save George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George looks up, surprised.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: You what?
{DIALOGUE}: To save me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I did, didn't I?
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't go through with it, did you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Go through with what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Suicide.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and the tollkeeper react to this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOLLKEEPER
{DIALOGUE}: It's against the law to commit suicide around here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, it's against the law where I come from, too.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOLLKEEPER
{DIALOGUE}: Where do you come from?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans forward to spit, but is stopped by Clarence's next statement.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Heaven.
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: I had to act quickly; that's why I jumped in.
{DIALOGUE}: I knew if I were drowning you'd try to save me.
{DIALOGUE}: And you see, you did, and that's how I saved you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tollkeeper becomes increasingly nervous.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George casually looks at the strange smiling little man a second time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (offhand)
{DIALOGUE}: Very funny.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Your lip's bleeding, George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George's hand goes to his mouth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, I got a bust in the jaw in answer to a prayer a little bit ago.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (comes around to George)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no – no – no.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm the answer to your prayer.
{DIALOGUE}: That's why I was sent down here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (casually interested)
{DIALOGUE}: How do you know my name?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I know all about you.
{DIALOGUE}: I've watched you grow up from a little boy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What are you, a mind reader or something?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, who are you, then?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Clarence Odbody, A-S-2.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Odbody... A-S-2.
{DIALOGUE}: What's that A-S-2?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Angel, Second Class.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tollkeeper's chair slips out from under him with a crash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has been leaning against the wall on it, tipped back on two legs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tollkeeper rises and makes his way warily out the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From his expression he looks like he'll call the nearest cop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (to tollkeeper)
{DIALOGUE}: Cheerio, my good man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George rubs his head with his hand, to clear his mind.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, brother.
{DIALOGUE}: I wonder what Martini put in those drinks?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks up at Clarence standing beside him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, what's with you?
{DIALOGUE}: What did you say just a minute ago?
{DIALOGUE}: Why'd you want to save me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: That's what I was sent down for.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm your guardian angel.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I wouldn't be a bit surprised.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Ridiculous of you to think of killing yourself for money.
{DIALOGUE}: Eight thousand dollars.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (bewildered)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah... just things like that.
{DIALOGUE}: Now how'd you know that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: I told you – I'm your guardian angel.
{DIALOGUE}: I know everything about you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, you look about like the kind of an angel I'd get.
{DIALOGUE}: Sort of a fallen angel, aren't you?
{DIALOGUE}: What happened to your wings?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: I haven't won my wings yet.
{DIALOGUE}: That's why I'm an angel Second Class.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know whether I like it very much being seen around with an angel without any wings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I've got to earn them, and you'll help me, won't you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (humoring him)
{DIALOGUE}: Sure, sure.
{DIALOGUE}: How?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: By letting me help you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Only one way you can help me.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't happen to have eight thousand bucks on you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no, no.
{DIALOGUE}: We don't use money in Heaven.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, that's right, I keep forgetting.
{DIALOGUE}: Comes in pretty handy down here, bub.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, tut, tut, tut.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I found it out a little late.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm worth more dead than alive.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Now look, you mustn't talk like that.
{DIALOGUE}: I won't get my wings with that attitude.
{DIALOGUE}: You just don't know all that you've done.
{DIALOGUE}: If it hadn't been for you...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (interrupts)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, if it hadn't been for me, everybody'd be a lot better off.
{DIALOGUE}: My wife, and my kids and my friends.
{META_DATA}: (annoyed with Clarence)
{DIALOGUE}: Look, little fellow, go off and haunt somebody else, will you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: No, you don't understand.
{DIALOGUE}: I've got my job...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (savagely)
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, shut up, will you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence is not getting far with George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He glances up, paces across the room, thoughtfully.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: Hmmm, this isn't going to be so easy.
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: So you still think killing yourself would make everyone feel happier, eh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (dejectedly)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: I guess you're right.
{DIALOGUE}: I suppose it would have been better if I'd never been born at all.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: What'd you say?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I said I wish I'd never been born.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, you mustn't say things like that.
{DIALOGUE}: You...
{META_DATA}: (gets an idea)
{DIALOGUE}: ...wait a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: Wait a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: That's an idea.
{META_DATA}: (glances up toward Heaven)
{DIALOGUE}: What do you think?
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, that'll do it.
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: You've got your wish.
{DIALOGUE}: You've never been born.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Clarence speaks this line, the snow stops falling outside the building, a strong wind springs up which blows open the door to the shack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence runs to close the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (looking upward)
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have to make all that fuss about it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Clarence speaks, George cocks his head curiously, favoring his deaf ear, more interested in his hearing than in what Clarence has said.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What did you say?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: You've never been born.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't exist.
{DIALOGUE}: You haven't a care in the world.
