{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence slowly follows him, glancing up toward Heaven as he goes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: How'm I doing, Joseph.
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks.
{META_DATA}: (pause)
{DIALOGUE}: No, I didn't have a drink!
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT – GEORGE MOVES INTO THE SCENE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sign bearing the name of the town reads: "Pottersville."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George looks at it in surprise, then starts up the street toward the main part of town.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he goes, CAMERA MOVES WITH him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The character of the place has completely changed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Where before it was a quiet, orderly small town, it has now become in nature like a frontier village.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see a SERIES OF SHOTS of night clubs, cafes, bars, liquor stores, pool halls and the like, with blaring jazz MUSIC issuing from the majority of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The motion picture theatre has become a burlesque house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gower's drugstore is now a pawnbroker's establishment, and so on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stops before what used to be the offices of the Building and Loan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a garish electric sign over the entrance reading: "Welcome Jitterbugs."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A crowd of people are watching the police, who are raiding the place, and dragging out a number of screaming women, whom they throw into a patrol wagon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George talks to one of the cops:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey... hey.
{DIALOGUE}: Where did the Building and Loan move to?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COP
{DIALOGUE}: The Building and what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: The Bailey Building and Loan.
{DIALOGUE}: It was up there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COP
{DIALOGUE}: They went out of business years ago.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSEUP
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George sees the struggling figure of Violet Bick, arrayed as a tart, being dragged into the patrol wagon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Violet!
{META_DATA}: (to the cop)
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, listen – that's Violet Bick!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COP
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I know that girl!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cop shoves George to one side.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks around and sees Ernie's taxi cruising slowly by.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Ernie – Ernie!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie stops the cab, and George enters it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Ernie, take me home.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm off my nut!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{META_DATA}: (a much harder Ernie)
{DIALOGUE}: Where do you live?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, now, doggone it, Ernie, don't you start pulling that stuff.
{DIALOGUE}: You know where I live.
{DIALOGUE}: Three-twenty Sycamore.
{DIALOGUE}: Now hurry up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Three-twenty Sycamore?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah – yeah – hurry up.
{DIALOGUE}: Zuzu's sick.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: He pulls down the flag on the meter and starts the cab.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CAB – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSEUP – GEORGE AND ERNIE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie is puzzled by the stranger.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Look here, Ernie, straighten me out here.
{DIALOGUE}: I've got some bad liquor or something.
{DIALOGUE}: Listen to me now.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, you are Ernie Bishop, and you live in Bailey Park with your wife and kid?
{DIALOGUE}: That's right, isn't it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{META_DATA}: (suspiciously)
{DIALOGUE}: You seen my wife?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (exasperated)
{DIALOGUE}: Seen your wife?
{DIALOGUE}: I've been to your house a hundred times.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Look, bud, what's the idea?
{DIALOGUE}: I live in a shack in Potter's Field and my wife ran away three years ago and took the kid... And I ain't never seen you before in my life.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Just step on it.
{DIALOGUE}: Just get me home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie turns to driving, but he's worried about his passenger.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he passes the burlesque house he sees Bert the cop standing beside his police car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Attracting his attention, he motions to Bert to follow him, indicating he has a nut in the back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert gets into his car and follows.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GEORGE'S HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM LONG SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The taxi pulls up to the curb and stops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cab is parked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George gets out and looks at the house.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Is this the place?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Of course it's the place.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, this house ain't been lived in for twenty years.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George is stopped momentarily by the appearance of the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Windows are broken, the porch sags, one section of the roof has fallen, doors and shutters hang askew on their hinges.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Like a doomed man, George approaches the house.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CAB – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The police car has pulled up beside the cab, and Bert and Ernie stand watching George's actions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: What's up, Ernie?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know, but we better keep an eye on this guy.
{DIALOGUE}: He's bats.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie switches on the spotlight on his cab, and turns the beam toward the old house.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALLWAY GEORGE'S HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The interior of the house is lit up here and there, ghostlike, by Ernie's spotlight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No furniture, cobwebs, wallpaper hanging and swinging – stairs are broken and collapsed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In a voice that sounds like a cry for help, George yells out:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Tommy!
{DIALOGUE}: Pete!
{DIALOGUE}: Janie!
{DIALOGUE}: Zuzu!
{DIALOGUE}: Where are you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence suddenly appears leaning against a wall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: They're not here, George.
{DIALOGUE}: You have no children.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (ignoring him)
{DIALOGUE}: Where are you?
{META_DATA}: (then, to Clarence)
{DIALOGUE}: What have you done with them?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DOORWAY – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert is standing in the entrance, with his gun in his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie is a few feet behind him, ready to run.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: All right, put up your hands.
{DIALOGUE}: No fast moves.
{DIALOGUE}: Come on out here, both of you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Bert!
{DIALOGUE}: Thank heaven you're here!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rushes toward Bert.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Stand back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Bert, what's happened to this house?
{DIALOGUE}: Where's Mary?
{DIALOGUE}: Where's my kids?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{META_DATA}: (warningly)
{DIALOGUE}: Watch him, Bert.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, come on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (bewildered)
{DIALOGUE}: Bert – Ernie!
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter with you two guys?
{DIALOGUE}: You were here on my wedding night.
{DIALOGUE}: You, both of you, stood out here on the porch and sung to us, don't you remember?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{META_DATA}: (nervously)
{DIALOGUE}: Think I'd better be going.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Look, now why don't you be a good kid and we'll take you in to a doctor.
{DIALOGUE}: Everything's going to be all right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert tries to lead George away by the arm, but George struggles with him, trying to explain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Bert, now listen to me.
{DIALOGUE}: Ernie, will you take me over to my mother's house?
{DIALOGUE}: Bert, listen!
{META_DATA}: (gesturing to Clarence)
{DIALOGUE}: It's that fellow there – he says he's an angel – he's tried to hypnotize me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: I hate to do this, fella.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert raises his gun to hit George on the head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he does so, Clarence darts in and fixes his teeth in Bert's wrist, forcing him to let George go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Run... George!
{DIALOGUE}: Run, George!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George dashes out of the house and down the street, as Bert grapples with Clarence, and they fall to the ground, wrestling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Bert kneeling, trying to put handcuffs on Clarence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Help!
{DIALOGUE}: Joseph, help!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, shut up!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Help, oh Joseph, help!
{DIALOGUE}: Joseph!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly Clarence disappears from under Bert's hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert gets up, amazed by his vanishing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Where'd he go?
{DIALOGUE}: Where'd he go?
{DIALOGUE}: I had him right here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie's hair is now standing on end with fright.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{META_DATA}: (stammering)
{DIALOGUE}: I need a drink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He runs out of the scene.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Well, which way'd they go?
{DIALOGUE}: Help me find 'em.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BAILEY HOME – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George runs up the path to the front door of the house and raps on the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rings the bell and taps on the glass, when his attention is caught by a sign on the wall reading: "Ma Bailey's Boarding House."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSEUP – GEORGE AT THE DOOR
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens and a woman appears.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is Mrs. Bailey, but she has changed amazingly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her face is harsh and tired.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In her eyes, once kindly and understanding, there is now cold suspicion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She gives no sign that she knows him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MA BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Well?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mother...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MA BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Mother?
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a cruel blow to George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mother, this is George.
{DIALOGUE}: I thought sure you'd remember me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MA BAILEY
{META_DATA}: (coldly)
{DIALOGUE}: George who?
{DIALOGUE}: If you're looking for a room there's no vacancy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She starts to close the door, but George stops her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Mother, Mother, please help me.
{DIALOGUE}: Something terrible's happened to me.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know what it is.
{DIALOGUE}: Something's happened to everybody.
{DIALOGUE}: Please let me come in.
{DIALOGUE}: Keep me here until I get over it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MA BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Get over what?
{DIALOGUE}: I don't take in strangers unless they're sent here by somebody I know.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (desperate)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I know everybody you know.
{DIALOGUE}: Your brother-in-law, Uncle Billy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MA BAILEY
{META_DATA}: (suspiciously)
{DIALOGUE}: You know him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, sure I do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MA BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: When'd you see him last?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Today, over at the house.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MA BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: That's a lie.
{DIALOGUE}: He's been in the insane asylum ever since he lost his business.
{DIALOGUE}: And if you ask me, that's where you belong.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She slams the door shut in George's face.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HOUSE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stands a moment, stunned.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then he turns and runs out to the sidewalk, until his face fills the screen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His features are distorted by the emotional chaos within him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Clarence leaning on the mail box at the curb, holding his volume of "Tom Sawyer" in his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Strange, isn't it?
{DIALOGUE}: Each man's life touches so many other lives, and when he isn't around he leaves an awful hole, doesn't he?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (quietly, trying to use logic)
{DIALOGUE}: I've heard of things like this.
{DIALOGUE}: You've got me in some kind of a spell, or something.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'm going to get out of it.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll get out of it.
{DIALOGUE}: I know how, too.
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: the last man I talked to before all this stuff started happening to me was Martini.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: You know where he lives?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Sure I know where he lives.
{DIALOGUE}: He lives in Bailey Park.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They walk out of scene.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CEMETERY – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Clarence approach the tree from which the "Bailey Park" sign once hung.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now it is just outside a cemetery, with graves where the houses used to be.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Are you sure this is Bailey Park?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I'm not sure of anything anymore.
{DIALOGUE}: All I know is this should be Bailey Park.
{DIALOGUE}: But where are the houses?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two walk into the cemetery.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (as they go)
{DIALOGUE}: You weren't here to build them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE MOVING SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George wandering like a lost soul among the tombstones, Clarence trotting at his heels.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Again George stops to stare with frightened eyes at:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – A TOMBSTONE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Upon it is engraved a name, Harry Bailey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Feverishly George scrapes away the snow covering the rest of the inscription, and we read: "IN MEMORY OF OUR BELOVED SON – HARRY BAILEY – 1911-1919"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE AND CLARENCE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Your brother, Harry Bailey, broke through the ice and was drowned at the age of nine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George jumps up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: That's a lie!
{DIALOGUE}: Harry Bailey went to war!
{DIALOGUE}: He got the Congressional Medal of Honor!
{DIALOGUE}: He saved the lives of every man on that transport.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (sadly)
{DIALOGUE}: Every man on that transport died.
{DIALOGUE}: Harry wasn't there to save them because you weren't there to save Harry.
{DIALOGUE}: You see, George, you really had a wonderful life.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you see what a mistake it would be to throw it away?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP – GEORGE AND CLARENCE
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Clarence...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, George?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Where's Mary?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, well, I can't...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know how you know these things, but tell me – where is she?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George grabs Clarence by the coat collar and shakes him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: If you know where she is, tell me where my wife is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not supposed to tell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (becoming violent)
{DIALOGUE}: Please, Clarence, tell me where she is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: You're not going to like it, George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (shouting)
{DIALOGUE}: Where is she?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: She's an old maid.
{DIALOGUE}: She never married.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (choking him)
{DIALOGUE}: Where's Mary?
{DIALOGUE}: Where is she?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{DIALOGUE}: She's...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Where is she?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (in self-defense)
{DIALOGUE}: She's just about to close up the library!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George lets Clarence go, and runs off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clarence falls to the ground, where he rubs his neck.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLARENCE
{META_DATA}: (to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: There must be some easier way for me to get my wings.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. LIBRARY – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary comes out the door, then turns and locks it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see George watching her from the sidewalk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary is very different – no buoyancy in her walk, none of Mary's abandon and love of life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Glasses, no make-up, lips compressed, elbows close to body.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks flat and dried up, and extremely self- satisfied and efficient.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, as he watches her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary, on the sidewalk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks up, surprised, but, not recognizing him, continues on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary starts to run away from him, and he follows, desperately.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He catches up to her, grabs her by the arms, and keeps a tight grip on her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She struggles to free herself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary, it's George!
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you know me?
{DIALOGUE}: What's happened to us?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (struggling)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know you!
{DIALOGUE}: Let me go!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary, please!
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, don't do this to me.
{DIALOGUE}: Please, Mary, help me.
{DIALOGUE}: Where's our kids?
{DIALOGUE}: I need you, Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Help me, Mary!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary breaks away from him, and dashes into the first door she comes to, the Blue Moon Bar.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLUE MOON – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Small tables, booths, perhaps a counter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is crowded.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Many of the people are the same who were present during the run on the Building and Loan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary comes running in, screaming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The place goes into an uproar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George comes in, practically insane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some of the men grab and hold on to him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (shouting)
{DIALOGUE}: Mary...
{META_DATA}: (to men holding him)
{DIALOGUE}: Let me go!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary, don't run away!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Somebody call the police!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANOTHER MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Hit him with a bottle!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANOTHER MAN
{DIALOGUE}: He needs a strait jacket!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (from back of room)
{DIALOGUE}: That man – stop him!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (recognizing some of them)
{DIALOGUE}: Tom!
{DIALOGUE}: Ed!
{DIALOGUE}: Charlie!
{DIALOGUE}: That's my wife!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary lets out a final scream, then faints into the arms of a couple of women at the bar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, no you don't!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (screaming)
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George can't fight through the men holding him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Desperately he thinks of Clarence, and heads for the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Clarence!
{DIALOGUE}: Clarence!
{DIALOGUE}: Where are you?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SIDEWALK – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just as George breaks through the door, Bert arrives in his police car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gets out and heads for the door, to run into George as he comes out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, it's you!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He grabs for George, who lets him have one square on the button, knocking him down, then continues running down the street yelling for Clarence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert gets up, takes out his gun and fires several shots after the fleeing figure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{META_DATA}: (to crowd)
{DIALOGUE}: Stand back!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bert gets into the police car, and, siren screaming, sets off in pursuit of George.
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BRIDGE OVER RIVER – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MEDIUM SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same part of the bridge where George was standing before Clarence jumped in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The wind is blowing as it has all through this sequence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George comes running into shot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is frantically looking for Clarence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Clarence!
{DIALOGUE}: Clarence!
{DIALOGUE}: Help me, Clarence.
{DIALOGUE}: Get me back.
{DIALOGUE}: Get me back.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't care what happens to me.
{DIALOGUE}: Only get me back to my wife and kids.
{DIALOGUE}: Help me, Clarence, please!
{DIALOGUE}: Please!
{DIALOGUE}: I want to live again!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSEUP
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George leaning on the bridge railing, praying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: I want to live again.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to live again.
{DIALOGUE}: Please, God, let me live again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George sobs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, toward the end of the above, the wind dies down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A soft, gentle snow begins to fall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT – GEORGE SOBBING AT THE RAILING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The police car pulls up on the roadway behind him, and Bert comes into scene.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, George!
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: You all right?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George backs away and gets set to hit Bert again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, what's the matter?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (warningly)
{DIALOGUE}: Now get out of here, Bert, or I'll hit you again!
{DIALOGUE}: Get out!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: What the Sam Hill you yelling for, George?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Don't... George?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George talks hopefully – George touches Bert unbelievingly – George's mouth is bleeding again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Bert, do you know me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Know you?
{DIALOGUE}: Are you kiddin'?
{DIALOGUE}: I've been looking all over town trying to find you.
{DIALOGUE}: I saw your car piled into that tree down there, and I thought maybe... Hey, your mouth's bleeding; are you sure you're all right?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: What did...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George touches his lips with his tongue, wipes his mouth with his hand, laughs happily.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His rapture knows no bounds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (joyously)
{DIALOGUE}: My mouth's bleeding, Bert!
{DIALOGUE}: My mouth's bleed...
{META_DATA}: (feeling in watch pocket)
{DIALOGUE}: Zuzu's petals!
{DIALOGUE}: Zuzu's... they're... they're here, Bert!
{DIALOGUE}: What do you know about that?
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He practically embraces the astonished Bert, then runs at top speed toward town.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LONG SHOT
{DIALOGUE}: George runs away from camera yelling
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{META_DATA}: WIPE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RESIDENTIAL STREET – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George's wrecked car is smashed against the tree.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes running into shot, sees the car, lets out a triumphant yell, pats the car, and dashes on.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET BEDFORD FALLS – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George sees that the "POTTERSVILLE" sign is now replaced by the original "YOU ARE NOW IN BEDFORD FALLS" sign.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, Bedford Falls!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns and runs through the falling snow up the main street of the town.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he runs, he notices that the town is back in its original appearance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He passes some late shoppers on the street
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PEOPLE
{META_DATA}: (ad lib)
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas!
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas, George!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. THEATRE – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAN SHOT – AS GEORGE RUNS BY:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas, movie house!
