{DIALOGUE}: Not a smitch of temp...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALL – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Mary comes through the door, breathless and excited.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The four men are watching with open mouths.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Hallelujah!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (to the men)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{META_DATA}: (sees George)
{DIALOGUE}: George!
{DIALOGUE}: Darling!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. STAIRS – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary races up the stairs, where George meets her in a fierce embrace.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: George, darling!
{DIALOGUE}: Where have you been?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George and Mary embrace tearfully.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, George, George, George.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mary!
{DIALOGUE}: Let me touch you!
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, you're real!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, George, George!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: You have no idea what's happened to me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: You have no idea what happened...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stops her with a kiss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She leads him excitedly down the stairs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, come on, George, come on downstairs quick.
{DIALOGUE}: They're on their way.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LIVING ROOM – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary leads George, who is carrying a couple of the kids on his back, to a position in front of the Christmas tree.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Come on in here now.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, you stand right over here, by the tree.
{DIALOGUE}: Right there, and don't move, don't move.
{DIALOGUE}: I hear 'em now, George, it's a miracle!
{DIALOGUE}: It's a miracle!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She runs toward front door and flings it open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ad lib SOUNDS of an excited crowd can be heard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy, face flushed, covered with snow, and carrying a clothes basket filled with money, bursts in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is followed by Ernie, and about twenty more townspeople.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{DIALOGUE}: Come in, Uncle Billy!
{DIALOGUE}: Everybody!
{DIALOGUE}: In here!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy Mary and the crowd come into the living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A table stands in front of George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George picks up Zuzu to protect her from the mob.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle Billy dumps the basketful of money out onto the table – the money overflows and falls all over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{DIALOGUE}: Isn't it wonderful?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The rest of the crowd all greet George with greetings and smiles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Each one comes forward with money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In their pockets, in shoe boxes, in coffee pots.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Money pours onto the table – pennies, dimes, quarters, dollar bills – small money, but lots of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Bailey and Mrs. Hatch push toward George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: More people come in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The place becomes a bedlam.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shouts of "Gangway – gangway" as a new bunch comes in and pours out its money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mary stands next to George, watching him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George stands there overcome and speechless as he holds Zuzu.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he sees the familiar faces, he gives them sick grins.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tears course down his face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His lips frame their names as he greets them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE BILLY
{META_DATA}: (emotionally at the breaking point)
{DIALOGUE}: Mary did it, George!
{DIALOGUE}: Mary did it!
{DIALOGUE}: She told a few people you were in trouble and they scattered all over town collecting money.
{DIALOGUE}: They didn't ask any questions – just said: "If George is in trouble – count on me."
{DIALOGUE}: You never saw anything like it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tom comes in, digging in his purse as he comes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOM
{DIALOGUE}: What is this, George?
{DIALOGUE}: Another run on the bank?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Charlie adds his money to the pile.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: Here you are, George.
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie is trying to get some system into the chaos.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: The line forms on the right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Martini comes in bearing a mixing bowl overflowing with cash.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Martini!
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas!
{DIALOGUE}: Step right up here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Martini dumps his money on the table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARTINI
{DIALOGUE}: I busted the juke-box, too!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Gower enters with a large glass jar jammed full of notes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Gower!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GOWER
{META_DATA}: (to George)
{DIALOGUE}: I made the rounds of my charge accounts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Violet Bick arrives, and takes out the money George had given her for her trip to New York.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Violet Bick!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VIOLET
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not going to go, George.
{DIALOGUE}: I changed my mind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Annie, the colored maid, enters, digging money out of a long black stocking.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNIE
{DIALOGUE}: I've been saving this money for a divorce, if ever I get a husband.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Partridge, the high school principal, is the next donor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARTRIDGE
{DIALOGUE}: There you are, George.
{DIALOGUE}: I got the faculty all up out of bed.
{META_DATA}: (hands his watch to Zuzu)
{DIALOGUE}: And here's something for you to play with.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN
{META_DATA}: (giving money)
{DIALOGUE}: I wouldn't have a roof over my head if it wasn't for you, George.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie is reading a telegram he has just received.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ERNIE
{DIALOGUE}: Just a minute.
{DIALOGUE}: Quiet, everybody.
{DIALOGUE}: Quiet – quiet.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, this is from London.
{META_DATA}: (reading)
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Gower cables you need cash.
{DIALOGUE}: Stop.
{DIALOGUE}: My office instructed to advance you up to twenty-five thousand dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: Stop.
{DIALOGUE}: Heehaw and Merry Christmas.
{DIALOGUE}: Sam Wainwright.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd breaks into a cheer as Ernie drops the telegram on top of the pile of money on the table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (calling out)
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Martini.
{DIALOGUE}: How about some wine?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As various members of the family bring out a punch bowl and glasses, Janie sits down at the piano and strikes a chord.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She starts playing "Hark!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Herald Angels Sing," and the entire crowd joins in the singing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see a SERIES OF SHOTS of the various groups singing the hymn, and some people are still coming in and dropping their money on the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carter, the bank examiner, makes a donation; the sheriff sheepishly looks at George and tears his warrant in small pieces.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the midst of this scene, Harry, in Naval uniform, enters, accompanied by Bert, the cop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Hello, George, how are you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Harry... Harry...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{META_DATA}: (as he sees the money)
{DIALOGUE}: Mary – looks like I got here too late.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BERT
{DIALOGUE}: Mary, I got him here from the airport as quickly as I could.
{DIALOGUE}: The fool flew all the way up here in a blizzard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Bailey enters scene.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. BAILEY
{DIALOGUE}: Harry, how about your banquet in New York?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I left right in the middle of it as soon as I got Mary's telegram.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ernie hands Harry a glass of wine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Good idea, Ernie.
{DIALOGUE}: A toast... to my big brother, George.
{DIALOGUE}: The richest man in town!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Once more the crowd breaks into cheering and applause.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Janie at the piano and Bert on his accordion start playing "Auld Lang syne," and everyone joins in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE SHOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George, still holding Zuzu in his arms, glances down at the pile of money on the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His eye catches something on top of the pile, and he reaches down for it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is Clarence's copy of "Tom Sawyer."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: George opens it and finds an inscription written in it: "Dear George, remember no man is a failure who has friends.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Thanks for the wings, Love Clarence."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARY
{META_DATA}: (looking at book)
{DIALOGUE}: What's that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: That's a Christmas present from a very dear friend of mine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At this moment, perhaps because of the jostling of some of the people on the other side of the tree, a little silver bell on the Christmas tree swings to and fro with a silvery tinkle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Zuzu closes the cover of the book, and points to the bell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZUZU
{DIALOGUE}: Look, Daddy.
{DIALOGUE}: Teacher says, every time a bell rings an angel gets his wings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{META_DATA}: (smiling)
{DIALOGUE}: That's right, that's right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks up toward the ceiling and winks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GEORGE
{DIALOGUE}: Attaboy, Clarence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The voices of the people singing swell into a final crescendo for the
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT
{META_DATA}: THE END
